(313, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'BONGAIGAON', 'rails-253134_640.jpg', 'rails-253134_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Bongaigaon is a city that is located in the Bongaigaon district of the state of Assam. The city is a reasonably well developed industrial centre and it is famous for its petro chemical industries. The place is being promoted as a tourist spot and there are a few places that one can visit while travelling to the city of Bongaigaon. The region is lush green and much of its natural beauty is still intact despite the industrial nature of the place. The main places of interest in the town are Bageswari Hill and the Bageshwari Temple. These are extremely popular among the tourists and are among the most visited sites in the area. One can also visit the Town Park that is located in the centre of the city. Kayakujiya Bill is located around 16 kms from the town of Bongaigaon and this is a popular tourist attraction. The place is visited by many foreign and local tourists alike every year. It is known for its natural scenery and there are many species of birds that are present in small islands that can be seen here. There are a few hill and stone carvings that can be seen in the district as well and these are also worth visiting.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">With the tourism sector on the rise in the whole of northeast India, the towns and cities in it are trying to increase their accommodation facilities as well. Proper hotels and guest houses are available here in Bongaigaon where people can halt and make themselves comfortable. There are many fine hotels in Bongaigaon which provide excellent facilities to the tourists.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Flight </strong>- Lokpriya Gopinath Bordoloi International Airport, located in Guwahati, is the nearest airport. This airport is located at a distance of around 100 kilometres from Bongaigaon</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- National Highway connects Bongaigaon with the states Bihar, Jharkhand and West Bengal. There are many Bus Terminals like ASTC Bongaigaon, Barpara Private and Chapaguri Bus Stand. There are many buses which connect Bongaigaon with major cities of Assam like Mangaldai Dhubri, Barpeta, Tezpur, Siliguri and Guwahati etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - There are two stations in Bongaigaon New Bongaigaon railway station the 2nd largest railway junction of Assam state and Bongaigaon old station. It receives trains from all major stations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport </strong>- Although auto and buses are available, it would preferable to book a cab for the day.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - NARAYAN, LOCATED AT BGR TWP - (FAMOUS FOR CHAT)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - BHARATIYA JALPAN, LOCATED AT CHAPAGURI ROAD, NEAR ICE FACTORY, BONGAIGOAN POLICE STATION - (FAMOUS FOR &nbsp;JALEBI &nbsp;AND SAMOSA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - MAYA&#39;S SWEETS AND SNACKS, LOCATED AT OPPOSITE OF BANK OF BARODA,, CHAPAGURI - (FAMOUS FOR SAMOSA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - CAFE DE JE&#39;UNERS RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT DEE BEE MARKET, B.O.C GATE, OPPOSITE HDFC BANK, CHAPAGURI ROAD - (FAMOUS FOR PIZZA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - BB&#39;S FOOD PLAZA, LOCATED AT NEAR HDFC BANK B.O.C GATE, NEW COLONY, MAHABIRSTAN - (FAMOUS FOR PASTRRIES AND CHIKEN SPRING ROLL)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - BONGAIGAON - {FAMOUS FOR MAASOR TENGA (SOUR FISH CURRY) ; &nbsp;MURGIR MANXOR JOOL (CHICKEN CURRY)}</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(314, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'CHIRANG', 'spotted-owlet-323976_640.jpg', 'spotted-owlet-323976_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Chirang district, covering an area of 1468.42 sq kms is a relatively new district of Assam. It was carved out of the districts of Kokrajhar, Bongaigaon and Barpeta in 2004. It is one of the four districts of Bodoland Territorial Area District (BTAD). The word &quot;Chirang&quot; is derived from the Garo word &quot;Chi&quot; meaning water and &quot;Rang&quot; meaning wealth. It is the second least populous district in the state, after Dima Hasao. Kajalgaon is the district headquarters. Chirang district is one of the 27 districts of Assam state in north eastern India. The district headquarter is in Kajalgaon. The name Chirang came from an old spelling for the Tsirang district of Bhutan.It is a new district formed in the BTC area of the state. Chirang district has been carved out from the erstwhile Bongaigaon district. The districts share its border with Bhutan.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">There are a few mid sized hotels and lodges in Chirang which offer neat and clean accommodation.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>By Air</strong> - The nearest Airport is the Lokapriya Gopinath Bordoloi Aerodrome at Guwahati.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Train</strong> - It is well connected by the Indian Railway network. The nearest junctions are Bongaigaon and New Bongaigaon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Road</strong> - Chirang district is about 200 kms from state capital Guwahatai. Daily day and night bus services are available to Chirang district from Guwahati.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - MOUCHAK RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT STATION ROAD, MAYAPURI, LANKA BETA - (FAMOUS FOR BURGERS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - ANANYA DHABA&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;, LOCATED AT NH31, SORBHOG - (FAMOUS FOR FISH FRY)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - TASTY RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT NEAR FONGBAI HOTEL, BALAJAN - (FAMOUS FOR CHOWMEIN)</strong></p>\r\n', ''),
(315, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'DARRANG', 'tahr-1751358_640.jpg', 'tahr-1751358_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Darrang is an administrative district in the state of Assam in India. The district headquarters are located at Mangaldai.The name Darrang was derived from the Bodo word Dourang, which means &#39;Lilabhumi&#39; the playground of Gods. According to Scholar Late Dineswar Sarma, the word Darrang came from Dawrang which means gate, as there was direct entry to Bhutan and from there to Nepal, China etc. Gradually this was known as Darrang. Darrang consists of a narrow strip of plain lying between Himalayas and Brahmaputra River in the northwest part of Assam. Darrang is an administrative district in the state of Assam in India. The district headquarters are located at Mangaldai. The district occupies an area of 3481 sq kms. The District of Darrang had been created with effect from July&#39; 1983 converting the erstwhile sub &not;division of Mangaldai. Recently this District has been divided into Udalguri District and Darrang District. The Udalguri District covers the major portion of this undivided Darrang District. This literature &amp; website however, still covers the undivided District. The word Darrang would mean undivided form of the District from this point and further. This district covers an area of approximately 3481 sq kms. Darrang District shares the border with Bhutan and Arunachal Pradesh. People of various communities live here with peace and harmony. Darrang District is in the central part of Assam.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Very limited options of accommodation available in Darrang district with a few hotels located in Mangaldoi.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - To reach Darrang District from outside Assam, one has to reach Guwahati by different modes like air, train or road. There are regular public buses plying from Guwahati to Mangaldai.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water </strong>- The district is benefited by the water transport system due to its northern boundary being covered by Brahmaputra River. There is steamer service from Upper Kurua to Guwahati.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - There is a wide network of roadways criss crossing the district with the NH 52 being the most vital, which is running through the district in east west direction connecting it with neighbouring Kamrup &amp; Sonitpur districts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - The Northeast Frontier Railways has a metre gauge covering 72 kms of the district connecting Rangia junction and Murkong Chelek.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air </strong>- The nearest airport is at Azara in Guwahati at 77 kms from the district headquarters Mangaldai. There is another Airport at Saloni in Tezpur which is at 110 kms east of Mangaldai.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - DARRANG - {FAMOUS FOR POITABHAT IS A BREAKFAST DISH MADE FROM RICE, CURD, ONIONS AND GREEN CHILLI ; BENGENA PITIKA IS A DISH MADE FROM BRINJAL, CHILIES, GINGER, ONIONS, CORIANDER LEAVES}</strong></p>\r\n', ''),
(316, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'DHEMAJI', 'holy-1195660_640.jpg', 'holy-1195660_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">One of the remotest districts of Assam, Dhemaji became a fully fledged district on 14th October 1989 when it was split from Lakhimpur district. With an area of 3237 sq kms, the district is bounded by the hilly ranges of Arunachal Pradesh in the north and east, Lakhimpur district in the west and the river Brahmaputra in the south. The serene location, paddy fields, the temples and the culture makes Dhemaji an experience in itself. The town&#39;s name Dhemaji&#39; is believed to be derived from a combination two Assamese words &lsquo;dhal&rsquo; meaning flood and &lsquo;Dhemaji&rsquo; meaning play. Dhemaji is a small yet very important district of Assam and it is located in the north east part of Assam. Dhemaji district borders with Arunachal Pradesh and is part of the Brahmputra plains. It is considered very important from point of view of archaeology. Dhemaji is inhabited by many Assamese tribes including Chutia, Ahoms, Sonowal Kacharis, Koches, Kalitas, Kaibartas and other tribes like Mishings and Deoris, so tourists can experience their culture and way of living. Abundant with rich green beauty and wonderful water bodies punctuating every place, it is a place which is waiting to be explored.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">There are plenty of hotels available in the city. There are many budget lodges in the town. But for those with no monetary restriction, there are plenty of excellent options.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">By Flight - The nearest airport to Dhemaji is Lilabari, near North Lakhimpur, some 66 kms away. Tourists can also go to Guwahati airport and take a taxi or bus from there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify">By Road - National Highway 52 passes through Dhemaji district. Dhemaji is approximately 430 kms from Guwahati, it is a 12 hour journey and Volvo busses are available on the route day and night. Direct busses are also available from Pasighat, Along and Itanagar of Arunachal Pradesh.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Dhemaji is well connected by rail to all parts of country. Trains are available from Guwahati and Alipur. Murkong Selek railway station is located in Dhemaji District near Jonai, a train from Murkong Selek travels along the meter gauge line via Dhemaji station and on to Rangiya Junction, Rangiya Junction also has broad gauge trains going to Guwahati, as well as Siliguri, Kolkata, Mumbai and Delhi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water </strong>- Ferry service available from Dibrugarh through Dibru Sonari Burisuti, Dibru Sissi Machkhowa Dibru Majarbari and Bogibeel Kareng Ghats. Ferries ply every hourly from 7:40 am to 4:00 pm from Kareng ghat and every hourly from 8:00 am to 4:00 pm from Bogibeel side.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Auto and buses are available for travelling in the city and also to travel to near by places like Gerukamukh.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - RESTAURANT CASA BLANCA, LOCATED AT NEAR NATUN NAGAR, NH-52 - (FAMOUS FOR MOMOS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - DHEMAJI JALPAN, LOCATED AT STATION ROAD, NEAR STATE BANK OF INDIA, RAM NAGAR - (FAMOUS FOR CHOWMEIN AND SAMOSA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - SONAM RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT NEAR RUKSIN CHECK GATE, JONAI - (FAMOUS FOR SOUP)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - MAMBOOZ DHABA, LOCATED AT NATIONAL HIGHWAY 37, NEAR M P JALAN PETROL PUMP, AMOLAPATTY - (FAMOUS FOR CHICKEN BUTTER MASALA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - MB&#39;S SWEETS AND SNACKS, LOCATED AT &nbsp;BABULAL PODDAR PATH, JALUKPARA, DIBRUGARH - (FAMOUS FOR KACHURI)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n6 - EAT REPEAT, LOCATED AT R.N.C. PATH OPP. OF RELIANCE TRENDS, DIBRUGARH - (FAMOUS FOR PASTA WITH RED SAUCE AND CHEESE DOSA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>7 - SHARMA SWEETS, LOCATED AT NH 38, DIGBOI - (FAMOUS FOR SAMOSA &nbsp;AND JALEBI)&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(317, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'DHUBRI', 'C26.jpg', 'C27.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Dhubri District is the gateway of western Assam happened to be in the past a meeting place of different racial groups which mingled together and formed a unique Cultural Heritage and Historical Background. The growth of blended culture in this region particularly in case of Language, Art and Religion is due to continuous process of assimilation of various races, caste and creed of local people, invaders and migrated people. Dhubri District is bounded both by interstate and international border i.e. West Bengal and Bangladesh in the west, Goalpara and Bogaigoan district of Assam and Garo Hills district of Meghalaya in the east, Kokrajhar district in the north, Bangladesh and state of Meghalaya in the south. Covering an area of 2838 sq kms including forests, reveries, hills etc the district has become the most densely populated district in India. Dhubri district is primarily dependent on agriculture and forest products. Main source of income is paddy with surplus production than its requirement Jute and mustard seed occupy the major share of cash crops. From forest mainly timber and bamboo add to the income though boulder and sand also available. Fish, milk, meat and egg have small contribution to the economy. Land revenue collection is very small in amount whereas excise duty occupies a lion&#39;s share of the Govt. exchequer. Tourism in Dhubri District is conferred with striking natural scenic beauties. Banks of Brahmaputra River with its abundant green fields, blue hills and hillock is almost like a feast to the eyes of the onlookers.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">There are several accommodation options like hotels and lodges in addition to in addition to government run lodges to choose from in Dhubri district with most of them being concentrated in Dhubri town.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - By boarding the Omni Buses at Guwahati, which are plying between Guwahati and Dhubri regularly, one can reach Dhubri. Buses are available for day and night. Dhubri town is situated at 290 kms from Guwahati, the state capital.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - From Guwahati the construction of Railway line is in the process. There is a train running between Dhubri and Guwahati in Meter Gauge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Dhubri has an airport at Rupshi which is about 15 kms away from the town. Now it is totally closed. The nearest operating airport from Dhubri is Lokpriya Gopinath Bordoloi International Airport in Guwahati.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - FOOD HUB, LOCATED AT LOAN OFFICE LANE WARD NO.6, BORO BAZAR - (FAMOUS FOR BIRIYANI)</strong></p>\r\n', ''),
(318, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'DIMA HASAO', 'bird-1038320_640.jpg', 'bird-1038320_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Dima Hasao district or Dima Hasao Autonomous Council is popularly known as the &lsquo;Switzerland of the East&rsquo;. It is a district garlanded by hills. This dreamland of the north east is an unending saga of undulating hills and valleys, gently flowing streams and waterfalls, lush paddy fields and bamboo forests where man and animal live in perfect harmony with nature. The exquisite hues of nature in the district blend beautifully with the hospitality of the local folks and makes the tourist experience highly alluring. Lush greenery, majestic hills and wandering clouds obscuring the mountains are a treat to the eyes. The rich cultural heritage of the district and its colourful festivals adds to the essence of tourism and makes the place immensely inviting. Haflong is the headquarters of Dima Hasao district, and is Assam&rsquo;s only hill station. In the local Dimasa language, Haflong means &lsquo;ant hill&rsquo;, an obvious reference to numerous termite mounds around the town.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">There are a few mid sized hotels in Haflong which offer neat and clean accommodation. Government run tourist lodge is a little away from Haflong. Tourists could explore the possibility of camping in Haflong with of course, the permission of Assam Tourism Department.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The nearest airport to Haflong is the Silchar Airport at Kumbhirgram. Silchar is located at a distance of 106 kilometres from the hill station and is well connected by road.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- Haflong has a meter gauge railway station at Lower Haflong that connects to Silchar, Lumding, Maibong and Jatinga. Lumding is located 131 kilometres from the hill station and many major trains stop at Lumding that connects to Guwahati.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- Roadways are the lifeline of Haflong. The National Highways 54 and 27 pass through the hill station and connects it to all parts of Assam and the neighbouring states of Meghalaya and Nagaland. While Silchar is the nearest and largest city, Guwahati is 309 kilometres away. Buses are regularly available from Haflong.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - DELICACY, LOCATED AT KALIBARI BAZAR, HAFLONG - {FAMOUS FOR PULAO, MAIJU( STICKY RICE), BAKHABUSU ( GOAT INTESTINE CURRY)}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - KHASI HOTEL, LOCATED AT DIBARAI, HAFLONG - (FAMOUS FOR RICE, BHAJI ,CHUTNEY AND PORK)</strong></p>\r\n', ''),
(319, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'GOALPARA', 'india-959646_1920.jpg', 'india-959646_19201.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The town of Goalpara is located in the Indian state of Assam. This town is located in the Goalpara district, and the entire district is an epitome of natural beauty. Goalpara district is situated entirely on the south bank of the river Brahmaputra covering an area of 1824 sq kms. Goalpara district was created in the year 1983 with two sub divisions viz Goalpara Sadar sub division and North Salmara Civil sub division, carved out from erstwhile Goalpara district. However, the same was again reconstituted in the year 1989 with only Sadar sub division of Goalpara. Tourists mainly travel to this town in order to unwind amidst the green surroundings and in order to relax. There are many places of interest in the district of Goalpara, and these can be visited during the trip to the region. Tourists can visit Dadan Hill during the trip to the town of Goalpara, and this hill is very popular among pilgrims. The reason for this is that the hill has a very well constructed temple of Lord Shiva at its peak. This temple is an old one and it was established by the King of Sonipur, called Bana. Tourists can also visit the Surya Pahar in Goalpara. There are many stupas and monuments of Buddhist importance in this part of town, and these can be visited as well during the trip to Goalpara. Goalpara also serves as a centre for many adventurous activities. Trekking and climbing are activities that are pursued here.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Tourists do visit this small town in Goalpara district and hence hotels are required for people for the accommodation. There are a few hotels in Goalpara where tourists can rest and relax and also enjoy its tasty cuisine.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Air </strong>- The nearest Air port is Lokopriya Gopinath Bordoloi Airport situated at Borjhar near Guwahati.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Rail</strong> - There is Goalpara town Railway Station in Goalpara which falls under the Northeast Frontier Railway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road</strong> - National Highway 37, NH 51 and NH 31B runs through Goalpara. Government and private bus facilities are available to Goalpara from Guwahati.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Local Transport </strong>- Bus and auto rickshaw facilities are available within the Goalpara town for local transport purposes.</p>\r\n', '', ''),
(320, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'GOLAGHAT', 'highway-332361_640.jpg', 'highway-332361_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Located in the state of Assam, Golaghat, an administrative district, is spread over an area of 3502 sq kms. Situated at an altitude of 100 metres above sea level; the catchment area of the destination is around 1220 sq kms. To the north of Golaghat lies River Brahmaputra and to the south lies the state of Nagaland. To the east it is bounded by Jorhat District while Karbi Anglong and Nagaon District are located to its west. Golaghat has derived its name from two words Gola meaning &lsquo;market&rsquo; and Ghat meaning &lsquo;the port of transport&rsquo;. This name originated during the mid 19th century from the markets that were located at the bank of the river Dhansiri. These markets were established by Marwaris, who belonged to the business class. When the British took over Assam, the Doyang &not;Dhansiri valley in 1846 was included under the Golaghat subdivision of Sibsagar District. In addition, the destination also played a crucial role in the freedom struggle of India. Some of the eminent freedom fighters like Kushal Konwar, Kamala Miri, Dwariki Das, Gaurilal Jain, Ganga Ram Bormedhi, Shri Tara Prasad Barooah and Rajendra Nath Barua, among others, were from Golaghat. Besides holding an important position in the freedom struggle of India, the destination is also known for its rich art and culture. Some of the important contributions made by literary intellects to Assamese culture are from this district. One of the most prominent writers of 19th century, Hem Chandra Barua belongs to this place. He was the writer of first Assamese dictionary, which is known as Hemkosh. The first Central Minister of Assam, who has the credit of translating William Shakespeare&#39;s The Comedy of Errors into the Assamese language, also belongs to Golaghat. One of the major attractions of the district is Kaziranga National Park, which partly lies in Golaghat District and Nagaon District.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">There are plenty of accommodation options in Golaghat district. Newer and better establishments are coming up regularly. A wide range of resorts, hotels, Government run lodges and guesthouses to suit every budget are available in Kaziranga and in Golaghat town.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - The national highways 37 and 38 are passing through the district. The NH 37 enters through Golaghat Nagaon border at Bagori and it passes through important places before entering Jorhat district at Kakodonga River Bridge. The Golaghat town, the district headquarters, is situated on the PWD link road between NH 37 and NH 39.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- Train services are available to Dimapur, Tinsukia, Dibrugarh and Guwahati. Furkating is the main railway junction in the district. A train service also operates from Golaghat town station to Jorhat District. Important railway stations in the district are Sarupathar, Furkating and Kamarbondha.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air </strong>- Golaghat district does not have its own airport. The nearest airport is Rowraiah near Jorhat at a distance of 55 kms from Golaghat town.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - MEAT AND EAT, LOCATED AT DOSS &amp; CO,KRISHNA BUILDING,GD ROAD - (FAMOUS FOR BURGER)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - SIZZLERZ, LOCATED AT MAGISTRATE COLONY, GOLAGHAT, BHOGA GAON - (FAMOUS FOR VEG AND NON VEG MOMOS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - Y2K DHABA, LOCATED ON AT ROAD, BOKAKHAT - (FAMOUS FOR BUTTER CHICKEN MASALA AND CHILLY CHICKEN)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - GOPAL KRISHNA SWEET, LOCATED AT AT ROAD, BOKAKHAT - (FAMOUS FOR PURI AND ALLU SABJI)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n5 - BALESWAR DHABA, LOCATED AT BAGARI N.C - (FAMOUS FOR CHICKEN AND MUTTON CURRY WITH CHAPATI (ROTI))</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - GOALPARA - {FAMOUS FOR PANCH PHORON TARKARI IS A DISH MADE FROM VEGETABLES AND SPICES ; POORA MACH IS A NON VEGETARIAN DISH MADE FROM SOLE FISH, CORIANDER LEAVES OR MINT LEAVES, CLOVES, CHILLI AND TURMERIC POWDER}</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(321, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'HAILAKANDI', 'munnar-1639120_1920.jpg', 'munnar-1639120_19201.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify"><br />\r\nThe town of Hailakandi is located in the Indian state of Assam. This town is a very popular tourist destination in the region, and many tourists flock to this place, as it is culturally rich and it has many important religious locations. The town is not very crowded, and can serve as the perfect base for people who are interested in visiting a sparsely populated region that has abundant natural beauty. Tourists thus see Hailakandi as a place to unwind and relax in. There are two major religious centre in the region which attract pilgrims from around the country. Tourists visit the town of Hailakandi because of its natural setting. The town of Hailakandi is located in a district of the same name, and the entire region is covered with thick forests. Almost 50% of the region is under forest cover, and these forests are primarily unexplored, and tourists can take a trip through them during their stay in Hailakandi. During the trip to the town of Hailakandi, tourists can visit the Siddyashar Bari Sibmandir, which is a very popular tourist destination in the region. This temple is located in the Badarpur Ghat region and Pach Pirr Mukan is another very important destination that one must visit during the trip to Hailakandi.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Hailakandi is a small town still untouched by tourists. The accommodation options this town offers are quite few including the Inspection Bungalow, Government Guest House or Circuit House. Apart from that tourists may also find few small hotels with just the basic facilities. For better hotels, Silchar situated 46 kms from town is the best option.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">By Flight - The nearest airport to Hailakandi is located in Kumbhirgram in Silchar. The airport is well connected to many other major cities like Kolkata, Aizawl, Guwahati and Agartala.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- Hailakandi is well connected to Guwahati via road located at a distance of about 330 kms. To visit the town, one can arrive at Guwahati via air, rail or road and can further take a bus to Hailakandi which is readily available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Badarpur in Silchar serves as the nearest railway station to the Hailakandi. Taxi, bus and Max service can be availed from outside the station till the town.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Hailakandi is a small town where hiring a cab is the best option to commute within the city. For short distance ride, auto rickshaws are also an option. And if up to some fun and sightseeing, cycle rickshaw can be used for commutation. At the end of day, whatever transportation one is using, this place will never disappoint with its beautiful culture and nature bounty.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>HAILAKANDI - {FAMOUS FOR OU KHATTA IS A &nbsp;SWEET AND SOUR CHUTNEY MADE OF OU(ELEPHANT APPLE) AND JAGGERY ; BAANHGAJOR LAGOT KUKURA (CHICKEN WITH BAMBOO SHOOT)}</strong></p>\r\n', ''),
(322, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'JORHAT', 'plantation-166515_640.jpg', 'plantation-166515_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Widely known as the Tea capital of India, Jorhat is one of the most important towns and one of the 23 districts of the state of Assam and is the headquarters of Jorhat district. The city is well known by its second name, &ldquo;Cultural Capital of Assam&rdquo; due to the presence of various cultural diversities in the area. Jorhat city guide is incomplete without a mention of its rich heritage. Jorhat was the last capital of the Ahom Empire. It is the home to several mythological monuments of Assamese civilization. The Brahmaputra River forms the biggest reverie island of the world which is located in the north of the district, Majuli. It is spread over an area of 924.6 sq kms. It had been the major spot of pilgrimage for Vaishnavites since the age of the Ahom Kingdoms. Jorhat district was carved out of Sibsagar district in 1983 and made a separate district. Jorhat is one of Assam&#39;s largest towns and derives its name from two haats or bazaars Macharhat and Chowkihat on either bank of river Bhogdoi, a tributary of Brahmaputra. The town gained in importance after Ahom King Swargadeo Gaurinath relocated his capital from Rangpur which present day known as Sivasagar in 1794. It was the last capital of the Ahom Kingdom and home to many historical monuments of Assamese culture. It was destroyed during the Burmese raids before the British began rebuilding in the early 1800s. Today, Jorhat is referred to as Assam&rsquo;s tea capital thanks to some 300 tea estates around. Many tea estates have colonial bungalows, some of which have been refurbished for high end, niche tourists.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">One of Assam&#39;s largest towns, Jorhat is Assam&#39;s tea capital. The accommodation options here are wide and varied from luxurious resorts to modest Government lodges and guest houses. There are accommodation options to suit every budget. Memorable stays among welcoming local people and stunning natural surrounds are guaranteed. Individuals and self help groups have established cottages and huts with basic amenities for tourist to absorb the state&rsquo;s rustic charm. Local cuisine, music and dance, hands-on farming, interaction with locals on farm management and techniques, home stays, visits to monasteries and forestlands are part of the leave your city behind package. Assam boasts of several enchanting old world tea bungalows with beautifully manicured lawns set amidst lush and tranquil tea estates. Several of the tea estates are now opening up their doors to welcome tourists for an unforgettable getaway. The Department of Tourism and Assam Tourism Development Corporation Limited operate lodges and resorts at various urban, rural and wildlife destinations.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Jorhat has its own airport named Rowraih Airport, which connects it to all major Indian Cities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Jorhat has its own junction named as Jorhat Railway Station which is connected to the major cities of Assam.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- Guwahati is nearly 6 hours by road. NH 37 runs through Jorhat. Road connectivity to Jorhat from nearby towns and cities or neighbouring states is good.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Assam State Road Transport Corporation (ASRTC) and some private travel service regular ply to access all major foremost places of Jorhat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Hired cabs are the easiest and most convenient way to get around. Daily Ferry Boats to the world&#39;s largest river island of Majuli can also be boarded from Jorhat and most of those travel arrangements can be made straight from the city hotels.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - NIMANTRAN RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT GARALI - (FAMOUS FOR BENGALI DISHES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - CRAZY HUT RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT GROUND FLOOR, M.M. PLAZA, K.B. ROAD - (FAMOUS FOR CAKE, PASTRIES AND CHOLA BHATORA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - BELLE AMIES, LOCATED AT GARALI, BABUPATTY - (FAMOUS FOR CHICKEN ROLL)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - LITTLE SOUTH, LOCATED AT KB RD, DOHABORA - (FAMOUS FOR DOSA, UTTAPAMS, AND SAMBHAR)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - EVER BAKE, LOCATED ON AT ROAD, KAKOTI GAON, TARAJAN - (FAMOUS FOR COOKIES AND GULAB JAMUN)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - SKY CITY DHABA, LOCATED AT BY PASS ROAD, BAPUJI NAGAR - (FAMOUS FOR COFFEE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>7 - CHENGMORA, LOCATED AT BARBHETA - (FAMOUS FOR CHICKEN CURRY AND PORK CURRY)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>8 - SUNDOR FAST FOOD, LOCATED AT GARALI, GAR-ALI - (FAMOUS FOR &nbsp;BURGER)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>9 - BREAK TIME, LOCATED AT CHARI ALI, T.R., TR PHOOKAN RD, CHOLADHARA - (FAMOUS FOR MOMOS, CHICKEN SOUP AND FRIED RICE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>10 - LAXMI SWEETS, LOCATED AT GARALI, BABUPATTY - (FAMOUS FOR SAMOSA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>11 - NATARAJ SWEETS, LOCATED AT JPR, GAR-ALI - (FAMOUS FOR RASOGULLA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>12 - CHERRY GARDEN, LOCATED AT K B ROAD, BABUPATTY - (FAMOUS FOR CAKES AND BISCUIT)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(323, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'KAMRUP', 'cherry-1459965_640.jpg', 'cherry-1459965_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Located in the state of Assam, Kamrup District is famous for the pristine temples of Kamakhya and Hajo that attract a number of pilgrims from all over the world. The District has been named after Kamarupa an ancient Kingdom in India, by which the state of Assam and its surrounding areas were identified in ancient times. The District is contains the major city of the region Guwahati and the state capital Dispur. Kamrup Travel Guide is incomplete without a mention of its rich heritage. There are many amazing and interesting places to visit in and around Kamrup. The Madan Kamdev temple has its own unique significance as it depicts about the origin of ancient Kamrup. Rice is the major crop of the district and it is very popular for silk and cotton clothes and for making of brass cups and plates. It is the major exporter of the crops such as coconuts, salt, betel nuts, piece goods and sugar. The district possesses a diversified culture of different religions such as Hinduism, Islam, Buddhism and Christianity. It is believed that the place was ruled by various rulers named as Hussein Shah, Vishwa Singha, Bali Narayan, Gadadhar Singha, Parikshit Narayan, Bijit Narayan and Gaj Narayan etc.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Though there are no good hotels in this district, there are comfortable Government lodges. As the bustling metropolis of Guwahati is nearby, people prefer to stay in Guwahati.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The nearest International Airport from Kamrup is Lokpriya Gopinath Bordoloi International Airport, Guwahati, roughly half an hour drive from the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Azara Railway Station is the nearest Railway Station from Kamrup and is located at a distance of 11 kms from the town. The second nearest Railway Station is Guwahati Railway Station, located at a distance of 30 kms from Kamrup.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Kamrup can be reached from Gurchuk cross road on NH 37 and is about 15 km from the city of Guwahati. The place is well connected with buses, trekkers and tourist taxis.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - HOTEL PUNJABI DHABA, LOCATED AT NAKUL NO-1, NEAR IOC RANGIA, RANGIA - (FAMOUS FOR CHOLA BHATURA)&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n', ''),
(324, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'KARBI ANGLONG', 'adventure-1844740_640.jpg', 'adventure-1844740_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The largest district of Assam, Karbi Anglong occupies an area of 10434 sq kms comparatively equivalent to the island of Hawaii. This large and charming hill district in the centre of Assam with its diversely rare flora and fauna has remained untouched and undiscovered. Diphu is the head quarters of Karbi Anglong district, located 172 kms from Guwahati. The nearest airport is Dimapur in Nagaland 54 kms away from Diphu. The district capital also has a railway station. The district has three sub divisions: Diphu, Hamren and Bokajan. The population of the district is predominantly tribal. The Karbis are the major local tribe who gives the district its present name. The Karbis are divided into three groups namely Chinthong, Ronghang and Amri. Karbi Anglong district is the largest amongst the 27 administrative districts of Assam state in north eastern India. The district is bounded by Golaghat district on the east, Meghalaya state and Marigaon district on the west, Nagaon and Golaghat districts on the north and Dima Hasao district and Nagaland state on the south. During the pre British rule the territory of the present district was part of the Dimasa Kingdom till the demise of Sengya Tularam Hasnu in AD 1854. It was during his time that Diphu present headquarter of district became a prominent town.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The largest district of Assam, Karbi Anglong occupies an area of 10434 sq kms comparatively equivalent to the island of Hawaii. This large and charming hill district in the centre of Assam with its diversely rare flora and fauna has remained untouched and undiscovered. Diphu is the head quarters of Karbi Anglong district, located 172 kms from Guwahati. The nearest airport is Dimapur in Nagaland 54 kms away from Diphu. The district capital also has a railway station. The district has three sub divisions: Diphu, Hamren and Bokajan. The population of the district is predominantly tribal. The Karbis are the major local tribe who gives the district its present name. The Karbis are divided into three groups namely Chinthong, Ronghang and Amri. Karbi Anglong district is the largest amongst the 27 administrative districts of Assam state in north eastern India. The district is bounded by Golaghat district on the east, Meghalaya state and Marigaon district on the west, Nagaon and Golaghat districts on the north and Dima Hasao district and Nagaland state on the south. During the pre British rule the territory of the present district was part of the Dimasa Kingdom till the demise of Sengya Tularam Hasnu in AD 1854. It was during his time that Diphu present headquarter of district became a prominent town.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road </strong>- The district is well connected with other districts through various routes. On the north it is covered by NH 37 and on the east by NH 39. The internal route from Guwahati to Diphu is 172 kms and bus services are available from Guwahati ISBT.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train</strong> - The local railway station to Diphu is served by North-East Frontier Railways and trains from Guwahati as well as direct trains from Delhi, Amritsar, Dimapur and Chennai are also available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Air</strong> - There is no airport in the district. The airport in Dimapur is 54 kms away from Diphu being the nearest to the district.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Diphu is situated at 270 kms from Guwahati. By roadways one can get buses from cities of Guwahati, Tezpur and Hojai to visit Diphu.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Local Transport </strong>- Having own vehicle is the best option. Hire a cab for easy travelling. Otherwise, auto rickshaw is the main mode of local transportation here.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', ''),
(325, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'KARIMGANJ', 'tahr-1751358_6402.jpg', 'tahr-1751358_6403.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Karimganj Town is a town in the Karimganj District of the Indian state of Assam. It is the administrative headquarter and main town of the district. Karimganj became a subdivision of Sylhet district of British India in late nineteenth century. It was severed from Sylhet during Partition of India and was included in India as a part of Cachar district in Assam. In 1983, Karimganj became a district of Assam with its headquarter at Karimganj Town. Away from the blaring noises of cities, Karimganj is a small sleepy town of Assam steeped in the beauty of nature. It serves as a perfect place to relax and unwind amid the lush green surroundings and besides the meandering rivers. Sharing its border with Bangladesh, the town is adorned with two major rivers Kushiara and Longai. A long rumbling canal called Noti Khal is also featured by the place which helps connect the two rivers creating a balance of the water level. Dotted with not many tourist attractions, a visit to the town of Karimganj gives you the opportunity to connect with the nature. The several forests near the town are waiting to be explored while providing the natural habitat for wildlife and birds.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">A small town of Karimganj does not offer too many splendid options for accommodation. It houses few budget and mid range hotels with just the basic facilities. Please avail the facilities offered by Assam Tourism Development Corporation Limited and Directorate of Tourism, Government of Assam for a comfortable stay. For better accommodation tourist often stay in Silchar.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>By Flight</strong> - Karimganj is a small town without its own airport. The airport at Kumbhirgram in Silchar serves at the nearest airbase to the town located at a distance of about 85 kms. One can avail a taxi from outside the airport till your required destination.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Road </strong>- This small town is easily approachable from other cities of the state via a network of well maintained roads. State owned buses as well as private buses runs regularly to Karimganj from Silchar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Train </strong>- Badarpur junction in the Karimganj district serves as the nearest railway station to the town at a distance of 32 kms. In fact this railway head serves as a main centre for the Barak Valley as well as southern Assam.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Local Transport -</strong> Karimganj is a place where one can easily hire taxi to commute from one place to another. With Silchar only 32 kms away, the transportation in and around the town is quite easy. However, make sure to plan the trip while keeping the weather conditions in mind and try travelling during the winter season.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', ''),
(326, 14, 31, 733, 'Assam', 'INDIA', 'KOKRAJHAR', 'tree-1458431_640.jpg', 'tree-1458431_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Kokrajhar is a town and an administrative district located in the state of Assam. The district of Kokrajhar covers a land area of 3169 sq kms approximately. Kokrajhar was earlier a part of the undivided district of Goalpara and was just a small village with only a train station to connect to the rest of the world. In the year 1957; a new civil division was created by then Chief Minister of Assam, Bimla Prasad Chaliha, who carved out the northern part of Dhubri sub division along with some parts of Goalpara sub division. There are people of different cultures and communities residing here like Bodos, Assamese and Rajbongshis, Bengalis, Garo, Santalis and other communities. The newly formed sub division of Kokrajhar covers a total area of 4066 sq kms with five tracts of Eastern Dooars, viz., Bijni, Sidli, Chirang, Ripu and Guma. The region of Kokrajhar faces a very humid and sub tropical climate, which is characterised by the lower Brahmaputra Valley of Assam. The climate is very suitable for the cultivation of paddy, which covers most of the agricultural areas in the region. Kokrajhar can be visited all round the year except the rainy seasons as the humidity is at its peak. The estimated forest area covered in the district comes to around 1719 sq kms, which also include the area reserved under the Aie Valley Forest Division of Bongaigaon district and Guma Range of Dhubri Forest Division. Popular attractions in the region of Kokrajhar are the Mahamaya temple, which is located at the border between Dhubri and Kokrajhar, Onthai located near the River bank of Gwrang, Bineswar Memorial park and Daimalu Park in Kharigaon.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Limited accommodation options are available in Kokrajhar district with a few budget hotels and lodges located in Kokrajhar town. Kokrajhar town also has a Circuit House.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>By Air</strong> - Though Rupsi Airport in Dhubri District at 76 kms is the nearest airport to Kokrajhar, it is not currently functional. However, Lokpriya Gopinath Bordoloi International Airport in Guwahati at 219 kms serves Kokrajhar.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Train</strong> - Kokrajhar Railway Station is located exactly in the middle of the city and is easily accessible from both sides of the station. This station is well connected to the other stations in Assam and in Punjab and 51 express trains stop at this station.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Road</strong> - Kokrajhar is well connected by roads. National Highway 31C passes 19 kms on the north and National Highway 31 passes 22 kms south of Kokrajhar. Tourists can approach Kokrajhar via Bongaigaon on the north and via Bilasipara on the south. State run buses, private buses and taxis ply regularly on these highways.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Bus</strong> - Kokrajhar is well connected by Assam State Transport Corporation bus network which connect Kokrajhar to most major cities in Assam, Bihar and West Bengal.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - MILOUHAB, LOCATED AT RNB ROAD, BAGANSALI, TENGAPARA - (FAMOUS FOR CHAUMIEN, MOMO)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n2 - FOOD PLAZA RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT SH 14 - (FAMOUS FOR COFFEE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - VLC RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT DEPOT ROAD, SUBHASHPALLY - (FAMOUS FOR BURGER AND SPECIALLY CHICKEN FRY)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - NISTHA, LOCATED AT DEPOT RD, WARD NUMBER 5, SUBHASHPALLY - (FAMOUS FOR KACHURI AND SAMOSA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - OMA RAJA BARBECUE CENTRE, LOCATED IN KOKRAJHAR - (FAMOUS FOR PORK MOMO)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n6 - TEPU FAST FOOD, LOCATED AT BAHALPUR KOKRAJHAR ROAD - (FAMOUS FOR MOMO AND CHOWMEIN)&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n', '');
