(477, 14, 31, 742, 'Karnataka', 'INDIA', 'TUMKUR', 'plumeria-rubra-344074_640.jpg', 'plumeria-rubra-344074_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">A city famous for its amazing religious destinations, Tumkur is located in the state of Karnataka and is an administrative district. The district headquarters are situated at Tumkur which is spread in an area of 10598 sq kms. Tumkur is a beautiful hilly area which is bounded by river valleys. Jayamangala and Shimsha are the major rivers which supplies its water to this place. The town is a very popular tourist destination which is majorly prominent for its natural surrounding and beautiful backdrops. Pavagada Fort, Aralaguppe, Lakshmi Narasimha Swamy Temple, Sree Siddaganga Mutt, Kalleshwara Temple and Goravanahalli Mahalakshmi Temple are the famous religious places of Tumkur. The Shivaganga hill is a renowned tourist place near Tumkur which is a conical structure with four faces and is very famous between pilgrims across the country. It is one of the popular tourist places in the state of Karnataka. Nestled in the foothills of Devarayanadurga hills with abundant greenery, Tumkur is a cultural and religious tourist destination in Karnataka. Dotted with many ancient temples, Aralaguppe is one of the temples dedicated to Lord Vishnu. An imposing temple with intricate work, it attracts people from all over India. Also within a short distance from here are four famous temples dedicated to Goddess Ganga. Take a trek up the Shiva Ganga Hills to bow in reverence to Lord Shiva the Creator. The two temples here are Gangadhareshwar and Swarnambha. The best time to visit the district is from October through March.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">One can enjoy a comfortable stay while on a tour to Tumkur. The city offers a remarkable blend of tradition and modern hotels. Tourists choose from wide choice of private hotels, lodges and rest houses at reasonable prices.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><br />\r\n<strong>By Air</strong> - The nearest airport to Tumkur is the Bangalore International Airport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- The town has its own Railway Station named as Tumkur Railway Station which is well connected by rail to all the major cities and states. The city is on the broad gauge train route from Bangalore to Shimoga and Hubli via Kadur.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - KSRTC and some private travel services ply between Tumkur and all other major cities &amp; states.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- Tumkur is easily accessible through road by NH 4. It is also well connected to all other cities and states.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - TUMKUR - [FAMOUS FOR BISI BELE BATH(IS A RICE BASED DISH) ; UPPITTU(BREAKFAST DISH MADE FROM ROSTED SEMOLINA ; HURALI SAARU( IS A SOUP MADE FROM HORSE GRAM AND VARIOUS SPICES)]</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(478, 14, 31, 742, 'Karnataka', 'INDIA', 'UDUPI', 'malpe-beach-172600_640.jpg', 'malpe-beach-172600_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">The name Udupi sounds quite familiar especially with the south Indians. For some, it brings to the mind the Udupi Krishna or Udupi Masala Dosa. Equally famous for both, Udupi is the city as well as the headquarters of the Udupi district, Karnataka State. Situated about 60 kms north of Mangalore, Udupi, considered to be one of the holiest places for pilgrimage in southern India, is the abode of Lord Krishna. Udupi Krishna Temple finds its place among the major temples like ISCKON Temples, Guruvayoor Temple, Dwarkadhish Temple, Dwarka Temple, Mathura Temples, Vrindava Temples- all dedicated to Lord Krishna. Udupi is the third most important city of Karnataka, in line with Bangalore and Mangalore. Most of the people of Udupi are engaged in agriculture and small scale industries such as food processing, dairy and cashew production. Fishing is another major occupation due to the vicinity of the sea. Udupi lies close to the Arabian Sea and the famous Malpe Beach is just 10 kms away from here. Lately Udupi is developing into a hub for the software industry. Udupi cuisine is popular world over and in most of the parts of India you can find Udupi restaurants, famous for dosas, idlis and other snacks. The tradition of this cuisine began in the kitchens of the Krishna Temple which serve meals in the form of prasada to the thousands of devotees who come to pray at the holy shrine.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Udupi town offers a variety of Private Hotels, PWD Rest Houses, Budget accommodation for boarding and lodging. Tourists can get luxurious hotels to budget hotels in the city to make the trip comfortable and enjoyable. Apart from this, people can also get budget hotels which suit their pockets. Along with the regular hotels in Udupi, the Mutts provide tourist accommodation at very low rates. Cottages are also available in resorts here.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>By Air</strong> - The nearest airports are at Mangalore that is 60 kms from Udupi and Bangalore which is 381 kms from Udupi. Mangalore is in turn connected with Bangalore and Mumbai.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Train</strong> - The railway station at Udupi falls on the Konkan Railway network. From the station, tourists can easily get a bus as well as a taxi for travelling to Udupi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Bus</strong> - Udupi is well connected with other neighbouring cities by Karnataka Road Transport Corporation buses. Regular bus services are available from Mangalore to Udupi. Tourist bus service providers ply luxury buses between Mumbai, Bangalore and Mangalore to Udupi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Road</strong> - Adjacent to Udupi are the NH 66 and NH 17 highways which make Udupi easily accessible by roads. The state highways connecting Karkala and Dharmastala, Shimoga and Srinari keeps Udupi connected to the local destinations within the state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Cabs and auto rickshaws along with local buses can be use to get around the city. Walking is also a good way to experience the local areas.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - UDUPI - [FAMOUS FOR GOLI BAJE(IS A SNACK MADE FROM VARIOUS FLOURS AND CURD) ; UPMA(BREAKFAST DISH MADE FROM ROSTED SEMOLINA), Pelakai Halwa ( Jackfruit Halwa) ; PELAKAI HALWA(JACKFRUIT HALWA) ; KEMPU KKAARA ALSO CALLED RANJAKA(IS A CHUTNEY PASTE MADE OF RED CHILLIS)]</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(479, 14, 31, 742, 'Karnataka', 'INDIA', 'UTTARA KANNADA (KARWAR)', 'sandbar-270772_640.jpg', 'sandbar-270772_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Located in Uttara Kannada district of the state of Karnataka, Karwar is a very beautiful and picturesque town of the district. The town has lovely beaches, beautiful temples and Forts attracting large number of tourists. The town is located at a distance of 15 kms south of the Karnataka Goa border and 519 kms North West of Bangalore. Karwar travel guide is full of references to the exhilarating places and serene spots in the city. It is regarded as one of the famous tourist places in the Uttara Kannada district. The region of Uttara Kannada is recognized for its serene natural beauty, gorgeous scenery, thriving green hills, magnificent mountains that are a part of the Western Ghats. The important historical sight of the town is Sadashivgad, a very famous tourist place situated by the Kali River Bridge at the confluence of the river and the Arabian Sea. Being situated at the border of Maharashtra and Karnataka, the culture of Karwar is a blend of both Marathi and Kannada cultures. The town is well known as &#39;Kone&rsquo; by the southern villagers, which denotes the corner of the region around the River Kali. As it is a natural harbour that lies in close proximity to the spice treasures of Kerala; the Portuguese, the British, the Arabians and now the Indian Navy have taken advantage of its location. The Kali River joins the Arabian Sea very close to Karwar, where the famous Sadhashivagud Fort has been built next to the Kali River Bridge. The river, the bridge, the fort in the distance and the gently swaying coconut trees paint a perfect picture for tourists.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Karwar offers decent accommodation options for visitors. Although nothing extravagant but one can choose from good beach resorts, budget or mid range hotels, guesthouses and beach huts. Karwar has multiple inns and resorts of different price ranges. Guesthouses, home stays and camps are also available.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><br />\r\n<strong>By Air</strong> - The nearest airport is Dabolim airport in Goa, 100 kms away from Karwar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Karwar has its own railway station. Karwar is well connected to Mumbai, Delhi, Ahmedabad, Mangalore, Cochin and other important places through the Konkan Railway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus </strong>- KSRTC and private buses services are available from Karwar to major cities, daily.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Karwar is well connected by National Highway 17 highway road to Goa, Belgaum, Hubli Dharwad, Mangalore and Mysore.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Car or auto rickshaw can be used to get around. Bicycles are also available for the eco friendly. Boats can be rented to visit some of the Islands.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - SWETHA LUNCH HOME&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;LOCATED AT ANANDA ARCADE, GREEN STREET - (FAMOUS FOR POMFRET TAWA FRY AND CHICKEN BIRYANI)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n2 - MARUTI, LOCATED AT RK TEMPLE ROAD, KODIBAG - (FAMOUS FOR VADA PAV AND BHAJI)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - TAJ FOOD COURT, LOCATED AT &nbsp;GREEN STREET, KODIBAG - (FAMOUS FOR COLD COFFEE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - ZAIKA RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT NAVAL BASE KARWAR, ARGA - (FAMOUS FOR NORTH INDIAN FOOD)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - PASEO GARDEN, LOCATED AT SADASHIVGAD, MAJALI - (FAMOUS FOR FRY FISH)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(480, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'KARAULI (HINDAUN)', 'fort-1287973_6402.jpg', 'fort-1287973_6403.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Karauli is a district in the state of Rajasthan and is situated at a distance of 160 kms from Jaipur. It spreads over an area of 5530 sq kms. The district was formerly named as Kalyanpuri after the famous local deity Kalyanji. The presence of more than 300 temples in Karauli makes it one of the holiest places of Rajasthan. As there was a danger of frequent attacks in the medieval times, the whole district had been built like a fortress. The district has a wall made of red sandstone in its surrounding and still stands tall, though dilapidated at a few places. The wall has 6 entry gates and bastions at various points, which further strengthen the structure. Karauli is situated at an average elevation of 902 ft and is covered with hills and ravines. The highest peak in the region is 1400 ft high. According to legends, this princely state was founded in 995 AD by the 88th descendant of Lord Krishna, Raja Bijai Pal Jadon. However, Karauli was officially founded in 1348 AD by the Yaduvanshi Rajput, Raja Arjun Pal. The district of Karauli is famous for its pale red stone architecture and boasts of various magnificent monuments like the City Palace, Timangarh Fort, Kaila Devi Temple, Madan Mohan Ji Temple, Mahavir Jain Temple and many other historic structures. The City Palace is an epitome of the rich heritage of the region. A major population of Karauli is engaged in making handicrafts, which are popular souvenirs for tourists visiting Karauli. The best season to visit Karauli is between September and March.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Karauli has budget hotels and resorts for the tourists and also for the regular visitors of the city who come here for business purpose. These hotels offer comfortable rooms, in house restaurants and other basic facilities to their guests at affordable rates.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Air </strong>- The Sanganer Airport, located at Jaipur, about 170 kms is the nearest airbase. Taxis are available from the airport to reach Karauli.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train</strong> - The Gangapur Railway Station, located at a distance of 35 kms, is the closest rail head to Karauli. As this is a major railway station, trains to all the important railheads of India are available from here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road</strong> - The locality of Karauli is well connected by the network of street to other foremost and secondary cities and towns of Rajasthan and rest of India. This locality is nearly 170 kms away from Jaipur, the capital city of Rajasthan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Daily bus services are available from Karauli to Gangapur and Jaipur. Many private bus agencies also operate tourist buses from Karauli to other important cities of Rajasthan.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', ''),
(481, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'ALWAR', 'india-1463876_640.jpg', 'india-1463876_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Alwar, a city of splendid monuments enchants the tourist with its charming appeal. Being a small town, it has imbibed the rich cultural heritage and is a great place to enjoy holidays. It is naturally decked with pretty water bodies and wild life this has always been listed as one of the outstanding locations in tourist&rsquo;s itineraries. Located in the state of Rajasthan, Alwar is situated on a ridge 889 ft above sea level. The city was founded by Raja Ajay Pal Chauhan in the 7th century. Situated in the Aravalli Hills, it possesses a rich cultural heritage which dates back to 1500 BC. Alwar which was earlier known as Mewat gained a remarkable reputation of art and culture under the rule of Maharaja Pratap. The imperial ambiance of the city comes from a number of structures and monuments of historical significance. It has beautiful lakes and valleys. It has one of the best wild life areas in Rajasthan. The city has a great architectural style. Forts and palaces with their magnificent decorations take away your breath. Beautiful lakes, big hunting lodges, historically important sites and several varieties of birds and animals etc makes this city a must see while visiting Rajasthan. Alwar is a hilly region located amidst the craggy rocks of the Aravalli Ranges in the state of Rajasthan. This place serves as the administrative headquarters of the Alwar district. According to mythology, the region was known as Matsya Desh where the Pandavas are believed to have spent the 13th year of their exile in disguise. Historically this place was also known as Mewar. Alwar is famous for beautiful lakes, grand palaces, magnificent temples, glorious cenotaphs, and towering forts. Tourists coming to Alwar can visit the Bala Quila, which is also known as the Alwar Fort. It was constructed by Hasan Khan Mewati in the year 1550. The masonry work and grandeur of the structural designs of the fort attract tourist&rsquo;s attention. The region of Alwar enjoys dry climate for the most part of the year. The best time to plan a holiday trip to Alwar is between the months of October and March.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Tourists can find a number of quality accommodations in Alwar. The variety of hotels in Alwar includes luxury deluxe hotels, budget hotels as well as heritage hotels. The tourists can choose the accommodation that suits their needs. Hotels in Alwar offer services and facilities to ensure a pleasant and comfortable stay. Many Hotels provide excellent services and facilities meeting with international standard.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Jaipur&rsquo;s Sanganer airport is the nearest one to Alwar at 162 kms. Jaipur is connected to many cities including Delhi, Mumbai, Calcutta, Jodhpur, and Udaipur.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Alwar railway station is situated in the heart of the city. It is well connected to Jaipur and Delhi. Some important train connections are available from Delhi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Alwar city is located on the State highway 25 and is close to the National highway 8. Through NH 8 Alwar gets connected to many popular cities of Rajasthan and neighbouring states. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Alwar is well connected to all cities in Rajasthan by state owned (RSRTC) bus services. Special private buses are available to Alwar from Jaipur. Bus facilities are viable from 5:00 am to 10:00 pm in most of the days.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Cycle rickshaws are the most common and available local transport in Alwar. Autos and taxis can be easily used for convenient conveyance. Buses also ply within the city.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - ALWAR - [FAMOUS FOR JHAJHARIYA IS A SWEET DISH &nbsp;MADE WITH SUGAR, CORN, MILK AND GHEE ; MIRCHI VADA (LARGE CHILLIES ARE FILLED WITH SPICED POTATOES) ; GATTE KI SABZI IS A CURD CURRY WITH GRAM FLOUR AND FLAVOURED WITH SPICES]</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - BABA THAKUR DAS AND SONS, AT KALAKAND MARKET ROAD, MUNSHI BAGH, GHANTA GHAR, MAIN MARKET - (FAMOUS FOR MILKCAKE AND SWEETS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - DUDH MISTHAN BHANDAR, IN ALWAR - (FAMOUS FOR PYAZ KI KACHORI)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - KHALSA DHABA, AT TEJ MANDI NEAR PURANI TRUCK UNION - (FAMOUS FOR DAAL FRY WITH LACHA PARATHA AND EGG CURRY)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(482, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'BANSWARA', 'camel-1574449_1280.png', 'camel-1574449_12801.png', '<p style="text-align:justify">Banswara is a city located in the southern part of the state of Rajasthan. It is the district headquarters of Banswara district which is spread over an area of 5307 sq kms. Banswara located at an average elevation of 302 mts, was formerly a princely state which was founded by Maharawal Jagmal Singh. The place derives its name from Bans or bamboo forests in the area. The city is also called city of hundred Islands as there are a large number of Islands in the Mahi River that flows through Banswara. Banswara district, which was formerly a princely state, was ruled by Mahrawals. It forms the eastern part of the region known as Vagad or Vagwar. According to folklore, the region was ruled by Bhil ruler Bansia who named it Banswara. Later, he was defeated and killed by Jagmal Singh who then became the first Mahraval of the state. After the Indian Independence, the Banswara state and Kushalgarh chiefship, in 1949 were merged in the state of Rajasthan and Banswara were carved out as a separate district. August to March is considered the best time for visiting Banswara. The princely state of Banswara was ruled by the Maharavals. It is believed that a Bhil ruler named Bansia ruled the place and named it as Banswara. Later, after defeating the incumbent ruler, Jagmal Singh became the Maharaval of the princely state. Situated on a ridge 990 ft above sea level, the district is surrounded by Madhya Pradesh in the east, Chittaurgarh in the northeast, Udaipur in the north, Durgapur in the west and Gujarat in the southwest.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Banswara has the facility of Government Accommodations and private hotels for tourists to stay. &nbsp;Hotels range from various categories for the visitors to choose as per their budget. And it is convenient to stay in hotels located around the New Bus Stand, Old Bus Stand and at GPO Circle.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air </strong>- The nearest airport is at Udaipur 160 kms from Banswara. A helipad with the facility to land charter planes is at Talwara around 13 kilometres from Banswara city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - The nearest railway station is at Ratlam 85 kms from Banswara. Ratlam is a railway junction and has meter gauge and broad gauge lines running through.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Banswara, the district head quarter has direct road links with the cities of neighbouring states like Ratlam, Dungarpur, Dohad and Jaipur. Transport of goods and commutation of the passengers are completely dependent on the road transport facilities in the district.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - State transport services of Rajasthan, Gujarat and Madhya Pradesh and the private travel transport operators ply frequent buses from Banswara to major cities.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - ARIHANT CORNER, LOCATED AT LANE NO. 5, RATI TALAI - (FAMOUS FOR ALOO BADA, JALEBI AND SAMOSA, BREAD PAKODA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - NATIONAL HOT AND COLD CAFE, LOCATED AT NH 113, OPPOSITE KUSHAL BAIG GROUND, RAJ RAJESHWAR COLONY, BHAGAT SINGH COLONY - (FAMOUS FOR JUICES COFFEE AND ICE CREAM)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(483, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'BARAN', 'baran-723896_640.jpg', 'baran-723896_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Baran, a popular district in the state of Rajasthan was carved out of Kota District on 10th April, 1991. The place is covered with forests of Sagavan, Kher, Salan, and Gargsari and the River Kalisindh flows through the region. It was ruled by the Solanki Rajputs during the 14th and 15th centuries. There are various spots in Baran that attract travellers from all over the country. Sitabari, Kakoni, Bilasgarh, and Shahabad Fort are some of the popular tourist sites here. Among these, Sitabari holds a great historical and religious significance. As per the Hindu mythology, Goddess Sita, the consort of Lord Ram, gave birth to their sons Luv and Kush at this place. It is believed that Sita, used to live here with her sons when she left Ayodhya. A temple dedicated to Goddess Sita is located here. Travellers can also see various water kunds in the vicinity of the temple. Sitabari Mela, a popular fair is held every year here. Some of the noted religious sites of Baran include the Bhand Devra Temple, the Brahmani Mataji Temple, and the Manihara Mahadev Mandir. In the Atru Tehsil of Baran, travellers can see the remains of Garhgachh. These include the ancient temples that were constructed between the 9th and 13th centuries. The Bhand Devra Temple is one of the famous shrines of Baran. Also, known as Khajuraho of Rajasthan, this temple is situated at a distance of 40 kms from Baran on the Ramgarh Hill. Baran too experiences a tropical climate. Summers are extremely hot, dry and unbearable while winters are very cold.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">There are a variety of hotels from different budget brackets and facilities to choose from. With tariff starting from 300/day going up to 3000/day, it is suggested that while booking the hotel, one must first compare the services provided, location and tariff etc. before finalizing the hotel.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The closest air base to Baran is located at Jaipur which is around 312 kms from the destination. It is well connected to major Indian cities including Mumbai and New Delhi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - The Baran Railway Station is connected to major parts of the country by frequent trains. The railway station is located at a distance of around 2 kms from the city centre.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Baran is well connected with all the important metro cities and other towns in India. NH 27 a part of east west corridor was earlier known as National Highway 76. It passes through Baran district.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Direct bus services are available from all major cities to Baran. Tourists can opt for AC or Non AC buses, depending on their budget.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>BARAN - [FAMOUS FOR DILKHUSHAAL OR DAL BADAM CHAKKI MADE OF ALMONDS,MOGAR(GRAM FLOUR),MAWA(CONDENSED MILK), BUTTER OIL AND SUGAR]</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(484, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'BARMER', 'jaisalmer-1502908_6401.jpg', 'jaisalmer-1502908_6402.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Barmer is an ancient city located in the Barmer district of Rajasthan. The city was founded in the 13th century AD by Bahada Rao or Bar Rao. The township of Barmer was originally named after him as Bahadamer which means the hill fort of Bahada. However, with the passage of time, the name of the city changed to Barmer. This region of Rajasthan is widely known for its rich handicrafts and traditional art forms. Various historical sites present here also make it a popular tourist destination. Filled with vibrant colours, rich heritage and warm hospitality Barmer is a small town representing the true reflection of Rajasthan all summed up in it. The sandy grounds of the town are lively and a must visit. Nestled right at the beginning of the great Indian Thar Desert, Barmer is a beautiful charming town that owns its fair share of rich historical past. Adorned with several historical sites such as lofty forts and palaces other than temples, tourists can always witness the rustic environment all around. &nbsp;Adding charm to the raw beauty of the town are the camels trudging along the barren terrain, artisans busy in showing their rich crafts such as pottery, weaving, wood carving, dance and music. Despite the harsh weather conditions and barren land, the place has attracted tourists from all around the globe displaying their brilliant craftsmanship especially in handicrafts, embroidery work and other traditional art forms.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Barmer offers many moderate hotels mostly located at the outer skirt region leading to Jaisalmer and interiors of the desert. Tourists can also find good hotels near the oil wells for as much as INR 500 to 750 per night. If a luxury hotel is the choice then they are mostly the palace converted hotels with all the luxurious facilities.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Civil Airport in Jodhpur, located at a distance of 207 kms from Barmer, is the nearest domestic airport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - The Barmer Railway station is well connected to the city of Jodhpur by metre gauge trains. Various trains to all the major cities of India are available from Jodhpur.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Barmer is well connected to other cities of Rajasthan by road. Buses and taxis are available to the region from all the major cities of the state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Tourists can easily hire a taxi, auto rickshaw or take a local bus to the required destination.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - DALLUJI NAMKIN, LOCATED AT JATIYON KA BAS - (FAMOUS FOR KAUCHORI)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - GAUR BRAHMAN BHOJNALYA, LOCATED AT SHASTRI NAGAR - {FAMOUS FOR LASSI (BUTTERMILK)}<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n3 - MANSAROVAR, LOCATED AT VIAD NATH MARG, KOTHWALI - (FAMOUS FOR ICECREAM)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - COASTERS, LOCATED AT BEHIND MAHAVEER PUBLIC PARK, NEAR TOWN HALL - (FAMOUS FOR COLD COFFEE)</strong></p>\r\n', ''),
(485, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'BHARATPUR', 'solar-panels-384165_1280.jpg', 'solar-panels-384165_12801.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Bharatpur is one of the renowned tourist destinations in India. It is also known as the Eastern Gateway to Rajasthan and is located in the Bharatpur district of Rajasthan. It is an ancient city, built by Maharaja Suraj Mal, in the year 1733. The city is named after King Bharat, brother of the Hindu deity, Lord Rama. Laxman, also a brother of Lord Rama, is worshipped as the family deity of Bharatpur. Bharatpur, also referred to as Lohagarh, serves as a passage to popular tourist destinations, such as Jaipur, Udaipur, Jaisalmer and Jodhpur. The district of Bharatpur is bordered by Haryana, Uttar Pradesh, Dholpur, Karauli, Jaipur and Alwar. Bharatpur is a popular city located in Rajasthan the state of colours and kings. It is widely known as the Eastern Gateway to Rajasthan. The place is located at a distance of 184 kilometres from the national capital of India. Maharaja Suraj Mal carved out the Jat kingdom of Bharatpur in 1733 AD. Apart from the rich heritage of Maharajas and past of India, the cultural heritage of the place is also very popular among the tourists. The scenic beauty of the place is mesmerizing and reflects the rich past of the Maharaja&rsquo;s of this region. The sunrise and sunset of the place is also very beautiful. Apart from the cultural heritage, royal past and scenic beauty, one more thing that grabs the attention of the travellers is Bharatpur bird sanctuary. Bharatpur bird sanctuary is the major attraction of the place. Here tourists get a wonderful chance to explore the endangered species. The flora and fauna of the place gives a thrilling experience to the vacationers.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Accommodation in Bharatpur is not a problem. All these hotels and resorts give royal treatment to the guests. The special cuisines offered at these places also add on to the good experience. The basic facilities at these hotels and resorts surely make people comfortable. The prices of rooms are affordable.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The Indira Gandhi International Airport at Delhi is the nearest airbase to Bharatpur. It is located only 207 kms away from the destination. Besides the Indira Gandhi International Airport, another option for tourists travelling to Bharatpur is the Kheria Airport in Agra.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Bharatpur has its own junction which connects all foremost regions of the state as well as neighbouring states. Tourists can opt to hire taxis from the railway station.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Tourists can also reach the destination by using services of the state owned buses, available from Agra, Fatehpur Sikri and Jaipur. Private deluxe buses are also available from New Delhi, Jaipur and Alwar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Autos and Tongas are the most widely used mode of transport within the city. Cabs are also available. Cycle Rickshaws are authorised to take inside the National Park as well.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - SHAHI RASOI, LOCATED AT MATHURA-BHARATPUR ROAD, KRISHNA NAGAR - {FAMOUS FOR DAL AND CHAPATI (ROTI)}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - SWAD RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT MATHURA-BHARATPUR ROAD, RANJEET NAGAR - (FAMOUS FOR DOSA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - DEVI RAM, LOCATED AT TARA MAHENDRA COLONY - (FAMOUS FOR KACHORI)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - PIZZA REPUBLIC, LOCATED AT PARISHAD ROAD, KRISHNA NAGAR - (FAMOUS FOR CHEESE PIZZA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - JODHPUR MISTHAN BHANDAR, LOCATED AT NEAR POWER HOUSE CIRCLE, PATPARA MOHALLA - {FAMOUS FOR LASSI (BUTTERMILK)}</strong></p>\r\n', ''),
(486, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'BHILWARA', 'jaipur-201749_640.jpg', 'jaipur-201749_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Located in colourful Rajasthan, Bhilwara, famous as city of calmness, culture and cloth lies in the region of Mewar. Situated on a ridge 1381 ft above sea level, the city is surrounded by Bundi and Tonk in the east and northeast, Ajmer in the north, Rajsamand in the west and Chittorgarh in the southeast. It is a unique city and is known for its good quality clothes. Widely known as the textile city of Rajasthan, Bhilwara is widely famous for its Fad Paintings. These beautiful pieces of art are made on cloth with natural colours. Bhilwara city guide is incomplete without a mention of the Mejha Dam, Harni Mahadev and Kyara ke Balaji and is also well known for its sweets such as Gazak and Makahn Beda. The city excels in the field of textiles and it is believed that there are more than 4000 textile manufacturing units in the city. Bhilwara holds a great name in the manufacturing of PV blended yarn and suiting. Bhilwara has been progressing at a very high rate in the state of Rajasthan and is one of the costliest cities of the state. The city has a quaint story of origin, carefully preserved by the locals. It is said to have come up in the middle of the 11th century when a Bhil tribal, supposedly one of the first settlers, built a Shiva temple on the site of the existing Jataun ka Mandir. This is in the area called Junawas, the oldest part of the town.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Bhilwara has some luxury and many medium to budget accommodation options. There are some of the deluxe hotels also with all facilities to make the stay a memorable one.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Bhilwara has well connected road network which connects all main cities of the state and also neighbouring state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The closest airport is at Udaipur about 165 kms to Bhilwara.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- Bhilwara has its own junction which is connected to all major cities and neighbouring states.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus </strong>- Local or state buses are easily available from all neighbouring states as well as foremost cities of the state to Bhilwara.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - Deviram Kachodi Wale, at Mori Char Bagh Road - [FAMOUS FOR KACHORI AND SAMOSSA]</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - Hari Bhai Kachori Wala, Near Punjab National Bank, Bhopalganj Market - (FAMOUS FOR FAMOUS FOR SAMOSAS AND KACHORI)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - Ajmeri Chat, Nagori Garden - (FAMOUS FOR PANIPURI)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - Pandit Ji Aloo Bada Centre,&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Near Pratap Talkies, Bhadada Bagh - (FAMOUS FOR ALOO BADA)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(487, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'BUNDI', 'sand-694990_1280.jpg', 'sand-694990_12801.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Bundi is a town in the Hadoti region in the state of Rajasthan. The town houses beautiful palaces and stout forts. It is a place, which has witnessed some great battles of historical importance. The architectural excellence of the town speaks volumes of the associated legends. This excellence can be seen in the form of step wells, locally known as baoris, and adorned forts and palaces. The town is endowed with rich natural beauty in the form of lakes, rivers and splendid waterfalls. Bundi is situated at a distance of about 35 kms from Kota and 210 kms from Jaipur. The city is surrounded by picturesque Aravallis on three sides. The huge wall surrounding the city has four gateways. The Indiragarh town situated in the Bundi district of Rajasthan is famous for Kali and Kamleshwar temples. The step well of Indiragarh offers one of the most beautiful sights to the visitors during rainy seasons. There are more than 50 step wells in the city which used to be the prime sources of water prior to the introduction of piped water system in the city. The scenic beauty of this place has been an inspiration for several poets and writers. Bundi is an important tourist destination in the state of Rajasthan, which has an amiable and inviting atmosphere for the tourists and visitors. Its natural beauty and picturesque palaces is definitely a treat to the eyes. It is considered as an oasis in the desert state of Rajasthan.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Deluxe hotels, budget hotels and guest houses are the accommodation options available at Bundi. The Rajasthan Tourism Development Corporation hotels in and around Bundi are good option to stay as well. RTDC hotels offer economy, deluxe and luxury rooms as per the tourist budget. The government paying guest accommodation available at Bundi is very economical and provides a feel at home comfort to the guests.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - If one wants to reach Bundi by Air, the nearest airport is the Jaipur airport, which is at a distance of 215 kms. One can make use of the taxi service up till Bundi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- The distance of Jaipur and Bundi is 206 kms. Bundi is well connected by NH 12 from Jaipur to Tonk, Bundi, Kota and Jabalpur.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- A small railway station is located to the south of the Bundi town. Bundi is well connected with Agra and Kota by trains. However it is most preferred to reach Kota Railway Junction 36 kms away from Bundi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Local Transport </strong>- Facilities like cars on rent, Auto Rickshaw and Buses are available for commuting. Private taxis, auto rickshaws, cycle rickshaws and Bikes on hire are available to move across the town. RTDC has many package tours offering to cover all the attractions of Bundi.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;">1 - BUNDI - (FAMOUS FOR LAAPSI IS A SWEET DISH MADE OF BROKEN WHEAT AND GHEE ALONG WITH NUTS, RAISINS AND DRIED FRUITS)<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(488, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'CHITTORGARH', 'india-1463864_640.jpg', 'india-1463864_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Home to the largest fort in India and the capital of erstwhile Mewar, Chittorgarh enjoys historical importance in Rajput history. Settled near the banks of Gambhiri and Berach, Chittorgarh is known to have contributed to numerous folk tales and fables.Chittorgarh is home to the Chittorgarh Fort, the largest fort in Asia. The Sultan Allauddin Kilji, one of the early Muslim rulers of Delhi coveted this land merely because of the famed beauty of the princess of Chittorgrah, Rani Padmini. The graceful but independent Rani preferred death to abduction and dishonour and committed jauhar which was an act of self immolation by leaping into a large fire along with all the other ladies of the fort. Located in the state of Rajasthan, Chittorgarh is one of the ancient cities in the region. This place is quite popular amongst the tourists all round the world due to its historical as well as cultural values. Moving in and around the city, one will find the thumbprints of Rajput tradition. It is said that Chittorgarh was founded by the Pandava warrior Bhima. It is a place which shows the perfect blend of beauty, love, grace and courage. When you are about to enter the city, you will be fascinated by the seven huge entries namely Bhairon Pol, Lakshman Pol, Padan Pol, Hanuman Pol, Jorla Pol, Ganesh Pol and the foremost royal gate known as Ram Pol. The following information is a Chittorgarh travel guide for people who are planning to visit this place. The city is also known as Chittor, Chittaur and Chittur. The famous markets being Rana Sanga market, Fort Road market and the Sadar Bazaar. Also, there is an annual Jauhar Mela held in the city. Chittorgarh was built by Maurya Dynasty in the 7th century AD and is mainly known for its beautiful forts and temples.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">There are Retiring Rooms at the railway station. Birla Dharmashala located within the fort provides the visitors clean rooms with basic amenities on nominal rent. Wide variety of accommodation is available at Chittorgarh. This comprises of Heritage hotels, deluxe hotels, Economy hotels, RTDC run guest houses, and circuit houses. Tourists can choose the accommodation as per their needs and budget.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>By Air</strong> - The closest airport is Dabok Airport in Udaipur at a distance of about 70 kms which linked it to all Indian cities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Train</strong> - Chittorgarh has its own junction which connects all foremost cities in Rajasthan and its neighbouring states.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Road</strong> - The city is well connected to different parts of India by road. The North South East West corridor expressways and Golden Quadrilateral Road pass through the city. It is also linked to National Highway 8 and in turn linked to major cities of Rajasthan and India by RSRTC and other private bus services.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Bus</strong> - Rajasthan roadways (RSRTC) or private bus services are easily available for visiting areas around Chittorgarh or accessing it from neighbouring state as well as foremost places of Rajasthan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Local Transport</strong> - Auto rickshaws are a good idea to travel in and around the fort. Cabs can be hired too. But it&#39;s best to travel on foot within the fort as one can see the fort in detail then.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - CHITTORGARH - [FAMOUS FOR GATTE KI KHICHDI IS A VEGETARIAN DISH PREPARED FROM RICE AND SOFT DUMPLINGS(BENGAL GRAM FLOUR) ; BADAM KA HALWA SWEET DISH AND VERY POPULAR HERE MADE FROM SUJI, GHEE AND DRY FRUIT]</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(489, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'CHURU', 'india-842025_640.jpg', 'india-842025_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Churu is a city in the desert region of Rajasthan state of India. It is known as gateway to the Thar Desert of Rajasthan. It is the administrative headquarters of Churu district. It lies in the Thar Desert on the National Highway 65 connecting Pali to Ambala and is a junction station on the railway line to Bikaner. It is near the shifting sand dunes of the Thar Desert and has grand havelis with marvelous fresco paintings, namely Kanhaiya lal Bagla ki Haweli and Surana Haweli, with hundreds of small windows. It also has some fine Chhatris. Near the town is a religious seat of the Nath sect of Sadhus where there are life-size Marble statue of their deities and a place for prayers. There stands a Dharam Stup, a symbol of religious equality. At the centre of the town is a fort built about 400 years ago. It is the administrative headquarters of Churu district. It lies in the Thar Desert on the National Highway 65 connecting Pali to Ambala and is a junction station on the railway line to Bikaner. It is near the shifting sand dunes of the Thar Desert and has grand havelis with marvellous fresco paintings, namely Kanhaiya lal Bagla ki Haweli and Surana Haweli, with hundreds of small windows. It also has some fine Chhatris. Near the town is a religious seat of the Nath sect of Sadhus where there are life size Marble statue of their deities and a place for prayers. There stands a Dharam Stupa, a symbol of religious equality. At the centre of the town is a fort built about 400 years ago.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Churu offers a range of luxurious as well as budget hotels and the architecture and the interiors of these hotels are sure to take one into the bygone era.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p><br />\r\n<strong>By Road</strong> - Churu is a town that is accessible mainly by road and it also has a meter gauge line running through the town. NH11 crosses the Churu city.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Train</strong> - The railway station is connected to places such as Bikaner, Jaipur, Delhi and a few other places. However the trains that pass through the station are mostly passenger trains and these are extremely slow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Air</strong> - The closest domestic airport is located in the city of Jaipur which is around 189 kms from the desert town. The Jaipur airport is well connected to most of the developed cities such as Chennai, Bangalore, Mumbai and Delhi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>By Bus</strong> - RSRTC or private buses are regularly available from all foremost places in the state Rajasthan or from neighbouring states also.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Local Transport </strong>- Cabs and rickshaws are available in Churu. Tourists can avail of cars for full day or on a half day basis to tour in and around the city.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - WRAPSTICK, LOCATED AT G.K MALL, NEAR SHYAM CINEMA, NAYA BASS - (FAMOUS FOR BURGERS AND PIZZA)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n2 - BHAWANA RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT NEAR CLOCK TOWER, MAIN MARKET, SADULPUR(CHURU) - (FAMOUS FOR KACHORI)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', ''),
(490, 14, 31, 752, 'Rajasthan', 'INDIA', 'DAUSA', 'animal-677668_640.jpg', 'animal-677668_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">The city of Dausa is located at an average altitude of 333 mts above sea level. Dausa is located at a distance of 55 kms from Jaipur, capital city of Rajasthan. Dausa is a part of Dhundhar region. Dausa district is surrounded with Sawai Madhopur district in the south, Alwar district in the north, Bharatpur district in the northeast, Jaipur district in the west and Karauli district in the southwest. Dausa is also known as Dev Nagari. Most commonly used languages in Dausa are Rajasthani, Hindi and English. Basanth panchami Mela is the popular fair in Dausa organized during February every year. Basanth panchami fair is celebrated for 3 days with a large local market for villagers to procure important requirements for the entire year. This festival is important to rural people of Dausa district. The district of Dausa was constituted on 10th April 1991 by separating four Tehsils namely Baswa, Lalsot, Sikrai, and Dausa. Dausa has given prominent freedom fighters to the nation. Late Shri Tikaram Paliwal and Late Shri Ram Karan Joshi were amongst the freedom fighters. Late Shri Tikaram Paliwal was the First elected Chief Minister of Rajasthan in 1952 after independence. The famous poet Sant Sunderdas was born in Dausa. Agriculture is the main occupation of the people of Dausa. The main crops of the district are wheat, bajra, rapeseed, mustard and groundnuts.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Accommodation available at Dausa includes deluxe hotels and Economy hotels. Tourists can choose the accommodation as per their needs and budget.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - National Highway 11 links Dausa to all major cities of the state via road. So, it is well connected to all foremost places in the state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Dausa has its own junction which linked all major places in the places as well as neighbouring states.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The closest airport is at Jaipur about 70 kms from Dausa.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - State or private travel services are frequently available from all major places in the Rajasthan to access Dausa.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - SURYA RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT GUPTESHWAR ROAD - (FAMOUS FOR ICECREAM, PASTRY AND FRUITJUICE)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '');
