(822, 19, 96, 1901, 'Hamburg', 'GERMANY', 'HAMBURG', 'hamburg-1340004_640.jpg', 'hamburg-1340004_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Hamburg has had a strong maritime tradition throughout its history including it becoming an Imperial Free City in 1189 AD and a cornerstone of the Hanseatic League in the years to follow. What to see in Hamburg includes theatres, museums and over 100 musical venues that the city is home to. Some of the better know Hamburg tourist places are the Deutsches Schauspielhaus, the Museum of Art and Industry and the English Theatre of Hamburg. Historic Hamburg tourist sites include the New Town or the Warehouse District both of which were established during the 17th century. Beyond Hamburg tourism, the city is also known for its port that is one of the largest in the Europe. It&rsquo;s functioning as a major hub for the banking, aviation and arts related sectors have resulted in many employment opportunities in Hamburg. The general cosmopolitan and friendly nature of the city makes visiting Hamburg attractions an enjoyable and memorable experience. Hamburg also known as Germany&rsquo;s gateway to the world for its docks and harbours the largest in the country is famous for Hamburg Pulses. The centre glows with masterful creations like the Hamburg Rathaus, while the infamous streets and shadowy alleyways of Reeperbahn in Sankt Pauli are famed for their gaudy strip joints and burlesque edginess. Meanwhile, the district of Schanzenviertel beats with student energy, Parisian style coffee joints, African world music, Chicagoan jazz and vegan kitchens all coalescing amidst its vibrant squares.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><br />\r\nHamburg&rsquo;s importance as a hub for media and industry professionals is reflected in its wide choice of business class hotels, many of which offer splendid lakeside views and rich in history. Cheaper options meanwhile can be found in less upmarket St. Georg, St. Pauli and Altona, as well as in the trendy Schanzenviertel district. These areas burst with character and offer out of the ordinary shopping and dining experiences at lower prices.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Hamburg attractions are easily accessible via the oldest functioning international airport in Germany, the Hamburg Airport. There is also the Lubeck airport in the neighbouring town of Lubeck with is serviced by low lost carriers and provide air connectivity to Hamburg.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Hamburg is well connected to rail services via Central station, Altona, Dammtor, Harburg and Bergdorf railway stations. Several Inter City Express train services operate between German cities alongside many direct trains to other locations in Europe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - The main bus stop is Hamburg&#39;s central bus station (ZOB) that is located near the central railway station. To reach Hamburg via the autobahn network is easy as the city is well connected by intercity bus services. Many routes operate that connect Hamburg tourist places to the rest of Germany and other cities in Europe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water</strong> - Hamburg is a major cruise port. Mostly during the summer months trips to Nordic countries are offered. However, there are also transatlantic services mostly to New York City.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Many Hamburg attractions are accessible via the dense network of bus routes, S-Bahn and U-Bahn operated by the Hamburg Transit Authority. Getting around in Hamburg can easily be done by taxi. With picturesque buildings, many historic places and loads of greenery, walking is a good way of getting around while sightseeing in Hamburg.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - HAMBURG - {FAMOUS FOR BIRNEN, BOHNEN UND SPECK IS A STEW MADE FROM PEARS, BEANS, BACON, POTATOES ; AALSUPPE IS A TYPE OF SOUP MADE FROM EEL (FISH) , VEGETABLES, HERBS AND FLOUR DUMPLINGS ; BRATKARTOFFELN IS A DISH MADE FROM POTATOES, VEGETABLE OIL OR BUTTER ; RODGROD IS A DISH MADE FROM &nbsp;POTATO, RED SUMMER BERRIES, BLACK CHERRIES AND SUGAR ; FRANZBROTCHEN IS A TYPE OF PASTRY MADE FROM BUTTER AND CINNAMON ; &nbsp;FRIKADELLER IS A TYPE OF DISH MADE FROM PORK, VEAL, LAMB, BEEF OR FISH AND SERVED WITH BOILED POTATOES AND GRAVY OR CREAMED CABBAGE}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - RIO THE GRILLBAR, LOCATED AT GRO&szlig;NEUMARKT 58, 20459 - (FAMOUS FOR BURGER)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - ZUM SPATZLE - SCHWABISCHER IMBISS , LOCATED AT WEXSTRABE 31 - (FAMOUS FOR CHOCOLATE CAKE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - DIETER SANCHEZ, LOCATED AT LANGENHORN. LANGENHORNER CHAUSSEE 174, 22415 - (FAMOUS FOR SANDWICHES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - O-REN ISHII, LOCATED AT ALTSTADT. KLEINE REICHENSTR. 18, 20457 - (FAMOUS FOR CHICKEN CURRY)</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(823, 19, 96, 1902, 'Baden-Wurttemberg 	', 'GERMANY', 'STUTTGART', 'stuttgart-69089_640.jpg', 'stuttgart-69089_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">The 6th largest city in Germany, Stuttgart is part of the 4th largest metropolitan area in the country. A historically rich city along with being an important economic centre, Stuttgart lies in the middle of a string of small towns surrounding it on all sides. The Stuttgart metropolitan area is one of the most densely populated areas of Germany. Stuttgart is a blend of medieval architecture as well as contemporary buildings. Not just a city for work, it also has many avenues for recreation such as nightclubs, opera houses, museums, libraries, parks, riversides and many others. Stuttgart also has an active nightlife which people from all over the world come to enjoy. Stuttgart has the reputation of being the cradle of the automobile industry as many of the initial breakthroughs were made here during the latter part of the 19th century. There are many automobile related museums here too, such as the Mercedes Benz Museum and the Porsche Museum, which are worth a visit. Stuttgart is home to many prestigious educational institutions for all streams, whether it is research sciences, music, arts or humanities. Stuttgart also has one of the most famous symphony orchestras based out of here the Stuttgart Radio Symphony Orchestra. Stuttgart spreads across a variety of valleys, parks and hills many of them covered by vineyards. This urban setup over a mosaic of landscapes is rather unusual for a German city. It often surprises visitors who primarily associate Stuttgart with its industrial reputation. Stuttgart boasts vibrant nightlife and cultural scenes. Calling itself the New Heart of Europe, this big city boasts plenty of things to do and is becoming an increasingly attractive holiday destination for foreign visitors. They flock here to experience the small town atmosphere, inner city architecture and suburbs filled with castles, wineries, breweries and landscaped gardens.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Stuttgart offers many affordable hotels, motels and apartments for short stays. &nbsp;Stuttgart&#39;s city centre offers a number of lodging options near major sites, but considers areas just outside the centre for better deals. For example, Stuttgart West is within walking distance from the centre and boasts fair share of cafes, restaurants, markets and theatres. Two more areas, Stuttgart Ost and Stuttgart Sud, are also centrally located and full of local character.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Stuttgart is very well connected via the Stuttgart International Airport, which is an important operations hub for Germanwings. Stuttgart is very well connected to multiple cities in Germany and Europe while being extensively connected to many international destinations. It is the sixth busiest airport in Germany.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - The main station within Stuttgart is the Stuttgart Hauptbahnhof, which is very well connected via the multiple high speed railways operating within Europe and Germany. ICE or Inter City Express is Germany&#39;s high speed train services with regular trains to Stuttgart from all over the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Stuttgart is very well connected to the rest of Germany as well as the rest of Europe via buses that run arguably on the best road network in the world. Stuttgart is connected from multiple cities within Germany as well as cities in other nearby countries via buses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - The state highways A-8 and A-81 form a cross near Stuttgart. The city is in the upper right quarter of that cross. West-east Highway A-8 passes Stuttgart slightly to the south, north-south highway A-81 passes slightly to the west.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Stuttgart has an extensive network of buses within the city and which are by the Stuttgarter Strassenbahnen. There are multiple cab and taxi companies within Stuttgart which can either be hired as a call taxi with on spot hire or booked beforehand as a call taxi. Stuttgart has a light rail system known as the Stuttgart Stadtbahn. Stuttgart has a well developed Suburban Railways network known as the Stuttgart S-Bahn.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - STUTTGART - {FAMOUS FOR DAMPFNUDEL IS A TYPE OF SWEET BREAD MADE FROM &nbsp;FLOUR, WATER, YEAST, BUTTER OR MARGARINE, EGGS OR SUGAR ; BUREBROT IS A TYPE OF BREAD MADE FROM FLOUR (RYE AND WHEAT), YEAST, MILK, WATER ; HEFEZOPF IS A TYPE OF SWEET BREAD MADE FROM FLOUR, SUGAR, BUTTER, EGGS, YEAST ; ZWIEBELKUCHEN IS A TYPE OF PIE MADE FROM YEAST OR LEAVENED DOUGH, ONIONS, BACON, CREAM AND CARAWAY SEEDS}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - WALDHEIM HESLACH, LOCATED AT DACHSWALDWEG 180, 70569 - (FAMOUS FOR MAULTASCHE IS A DISH MADE FROM PASTA DOUGH, MINCED MEAT, SMOKED MEAT, SPINACH, BREAD CRUMBS, ONIONS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - HUFTENGOLD,&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;LOCATED AT OLGASTRA 44&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; - (FAMOUS FOR COFFEE AND CAKE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - GELATARIA, LOCATED AT MARIENPLATZ 12 - (FAMOUS FOR SPECULAAS IS A TYPE OF COOKIE MADE FROM FLOUR, SUGAR, BUTTER, PEPPER, CINNAMON, GINGER, CLOVES, CARDAMOM AND NUTMEG)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(824, 19, 96, 1903, 'North Rhine-Westphalia', 'GERMANY', 'DUSSELDORF', 'ferris-wheel-2532337_640.jpg', 'ferris-wheel-2532337_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The capital of North Rhine Westphalia, Dusseldorf is a destination for artistic souls and major businesses alike. Part of the Rhine Ruhr conurbation, which includes both Cologne and Bonn, it&rsquo;s a place that&rsquo;s bloomed with culture over the years, offering a distinctive character and a wide range of activities. Although well known for its fashion and arts scene, the attractions of Dusseldorf are not just limited to its world renowned trade fairs or extremely rich culture. The city is located in western Germany and is famous for its nightlife, especially around the Altstadt, an Old Town along the river Rhine that is often referred to as the world&#39;s longest bar. Other things to do in Dusseldorf include visiting the Medienhafen, a newly developed harbour area known for its inspiring avant grade architecture or the Konigsalle, their main shopping street. The tourist places in Dusseldorf such as its many museums, theatres and restaurants get a steady flow of visitors all the year round with the busiest months being July, August and November when Carnival takes place. There are many interesting places to eat in Dusseldorf. Beyond the obvious, Dusseldorf attractions also include many opportunities in the corporate sector with the city functioning as a major hub for the fashion, advertising, telecommunications and banking sectors. The general cosmopolitan and active nature of the city makes it a good place to visit.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The Old City, Altstadt, is the centre of the action and offers a number of hotels and guest houses. For quiet evenings and a view of the Old City consider the Oberkassel/Niederkassel area on the other side of the Rhine River. There is inexpensive accommodation in the Unterbilk area near the university, along with a collection of bars, restaurants and cafes. For a more affordable option, consider a budget friendly boutique hotel or small bed and breakfast in one of the city&#39;s diverse residential neighbourhoods.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />\r\n<strong>By Air</strong> - How to reach Dusseldorf by air is never a hard task as Dusseldorf airport is the third largest and busiest airport in Germany. It functions as the main airport for the Rhine Ruhr metropolitan area. It connects Dusseldorf with over a 175 cities globally.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train</strong> - Over 1000 trains stop at Dusseldorf Hauptbahnhof making it a major hub for Germany&#39;s high speed rail network called Deutsche Bahn. The S-Bahn provides connectivity to the Rhine Ruhr metropolitan area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus</strong> - There are many bus services that connect Dusseldorf attractions to the rest of Germany and other cities in Europe. Some of the major private players providing bus services from Dusseldorf to other cities around Germany and the rest of Europe are Flexibus, Eurolines, Mein Fernbus and Dein Bus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Bus services are well integrated with the city&rsquo;s subway and tramcars, which are also operated by Rhinebahn. Dusseldorf can easily be fixed by getting a cab at one of the 150 taxi stands all across the Dusseldorf map. The subway and tramway are also well integrated with the cities bus services. There is a suburban railway system that operates in and around Dusseldorf providing it with connectivity to the surrounding areas.</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - DUSSELDORF - {FAMOUS FOR BLUTWURST &nbsp;IS A SAUSAGE MADE FROM PORK ; SAUERBRATEN IS A TYPE OF DISH MADE FROM MEAT (USUALLY BEEF, VEAL, VENISON), VINEGAR, VEGETABLES, AND SPICES ; AADZE ZUPP IS A PEA SOUP; WESTF&auml;LISCHER PICKERT IS A TYPE OF PANCAKE MADE FROM &nbsp;POTATOES, EGGS, FLOUR AND SERVED WITH SUGAR, BUTTER AND MARMALADE, OR WITH GROUND MEAT ; &nbsp;GRUNKOHLESSEN IS A DISH CONSISTS OF KALE, SAUSAGES, BAKED SWEET POTATOES, BACON AND MUSTARD ; WESTFALISCHE RINDERWURST IS A TYPE OF SAUSAGE MADE FROM BEEF, VEGETABLES, PEARL BARLEY, GROATS AND BUTTER ; RHEINISCHER DOBBEKOOCHE (DOPPEKOOCHE) IS A TYPE OF CAKE MADE FROM POTATOES, EGGS, SPICES AND ONIONS, WITH SAUSAGES AND BACON ;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - RISTORANTE ALBEROBELLO, LOCATED AT &nbsp;DOROTHEENSTRABE 104, 40235 - (FAMOUS FOR PIZZA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - JADE VEGETARIAN KITCHEN, LOCATED AT &nbsp;DURENER STR. 42, 40223 - (FAMOUS FOR SOUP AND SPRING ROLLS)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(825, 19, 96, 1903, 'North Rhine-Westphalia', 'GERMANY', 'COLOGNE', 'cologne-1078671_640.jpg', 'cologne-1078671_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Cologne, founded 2000 years ago by the Romans, is one of the oldest cities in Germany. The twelve Romanesque churches and the famous cathedral attest to how important the city was as a religious centre. Today Cologne has a relaxed, almost provincial atmosphere. Its historic centre is ideal to explore on foot. Besides the many ecclesiastic buildings the city also offers a number of interesting museums and historic structures. Anyone who&rsquo;s ever wondered where cologne came from need not worry any more. This type of fragrance is named after Cologne, the German city where it was invented. Germany&rsquo;s 4th largest city with one million residents, was heavily bombed during World War-II. As a result, Cologne is a quite modern city, though remnants of its rich history, dating from Roman times, can still be found. Located on the scenic Rhine River, this city is one of the most visited destinations in Germany and there are plenty of great tourist attractions in Cologne, both ancient and new. This lively city on the Rhine offers a wealth of cultural activities, international trade fairs and conferences, and numerous major events. Attractions such as Cologne Cathedral, which is recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, create an unforgettable impression on visitors. With shopping streets, alleys in the old town and characteristic urban neighbourhoods known as Veedel in Cologne&rsquo;s own dialect Cologne is considered an insider tip as one of Germany&rsquo;s greatest cities for shopping. And let&rsquo;s not forget the excellent and exciting night life among Germany&rsquo;s major cities Cologne has the highest density of pubs and taverns.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The Ring is a semicircular area around the edge of the city&#39;s walls from Chlodwigplatz to Ebertplatz. Along the semicircle are hotel chains and boutique accommodations that offers ready access to the city centre on foot or via a short metro ride. For access to nightlife, consider the Sudstadt area known for its rock bars, cocktails and theatres. The luxury accommodations in the elegant Friesenviertel area often attract local celebrities. Search for lodging deals in the Nippes area, which is away from the busy centre and known for its local character.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Air</strong> - Cologne Bonn Airport is an international airport and is well connected to all the countries of Europe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train</strong> - There are daily regional trains from all over Europe to Cologne. Cologne is served by two stations with the main one being the Koln Hauptbahnhof and is well connected to Amsterdam, Berlin, Brussels, Hamburg, London and Paris amongst other cities in Europe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Cologne has an International bus station Busbahnhof at Breslauer Platz. There are direct buses running to and from Cologne.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road</strong> - Plenty of motorways Autobahns A-1, A-4, A-3, A-57 and A-555 lead to Cologne. During rush hour the streets are heavily congested, also due to massive construction of a new subway tunnel Nord Sud Stadtbahn, crossing half the city centre.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Cologne has a very good subway and tram and bus network. Cologne&#39;s subway and tram system is a mixture between both systems, comparable to a light rail system with greater underground sections. &nbsp;It is also possible to rent a bike at many different places by bike is maybe the best way to go around in the city.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - COLOGNE - {FAMOUS FOR &nbsp;HIMMEL UND ERDE IS A DISH WHICH CONTAINS BLACK PUDDING (BLOOD SAUSAGE), ONIONS, MASHED POTATO WITH APPLE SAUCE ; HALVE HAHN IS A RYE ROLL MADE FROM BUTTER, CHEESE AND MUSTARD ; BRATWURST IS A SAUSAGE MADE FROM PORK AND BEEF ; SCHNITZEL IS A FRIED PORK OR VEAL MEAT, COATED WITH BREAD CRUMBS AND EGGS SERVED WITH FRIED POTATOES ; METTBROTCHEN IS A RAW PORK MEAT WITH RAW ONION RINGS ON A BREAD ROLL ; KOLSCHE KAVIAR IS A BLOOD SAUSAGE SERVED WITH ONIONS AND RYE ROLL}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - DAITOKAI, LOCATED AT KATTENBUG 2, 50667 - (FAMOUS FOR PASTRY AND COFFEE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - MANUFACTUM BROT&amp;BUTTER, LOCATED AT BR&uuml;CKENSTRA&szlig;E 23, 50667 - (FAMOUS FOR QUICHE IS A TYPE OF &nbsp;SAVOURY TART MADE FROM PASTRY CASE FILLED WITH EGG AND CHEESE, MEAT, SEAFOOD OR VEGETABLES</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - CAFE RIESE, LOCATED AT SCHILDERGASSE 103, 50667 &nbsp;- (FAMOUS FOR COFFEE AND PASTRIES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - DIE FETTE KUH, LOCATED AT BONNER STR. 43, 50677 - (FAMOUS FOR BURGER)</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(826, 19, 96, 1899, 'Saxony', 'GERMANY', 'LEIPZIG', 'leipzig-745365_640.jpg', 'leipzig-745365_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The largest city in Germany&rsquo;s federal state of Saxony, Leipzig is often called the City of Heroes for its leading role in the 1989 democratic revolution and the fall of the Berlin Wall. Leipzig is also known for its vibrant arts and culture scene shaped by famous music composers like Bach, Richard Wagner and Felix Mendelssohn. It has been a trade city since the times of the Roman Empire because it&#39;s placed on the crossroads of two important medieval trade routes, known as Via Regia. Tourists today can enjoy performances of Bach&rsquo;s music at the St. Thomas Church where Bach once served as choir leader and is now buried. In addition to numerous museums, old churches and historic sites like the Old Town Hall, the city boasts several of Germany&rsquo;s oldest and most impressive structures such as the Napoleonic Monument to the Battle of the Nations and Reichsgericht, the former high court of the Reich. One of Europe&rsquo;s largest town squares, the Augustusplatz, is situated at the central campus of the city&rsquo;s university, which is the second oldest university in Germany. What&rsquo;s more, Leipzig is home to Germany&rsquo;s oldest botanical garden and one of the country&rsquo;s largest zoos. Leipzig is host to a number of annual festivals such as the Bach Festival, the world&rsquo;s largest Goth festival and an international balloon festival. With a large flea market, a shopping mall in one of Europe&rsquo;s largest rail stations and a vibrant Christmas Market, Leipzig is a shopper&rsquo;s delight. For nightlife, tourists will find a variety of pubs, bars and dance clubs within the city, especially along the street of Karl Leibknecht Strasse, nicknamed Karli.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Leipzig has a large number of hotels and places to stay, including some very up market ones which are expensive but the facilities and luxuries they offer more than compensate for the price. There are aplenty options for midrange and budget hotels and places to stay as well. There is also ample choice for a budget traveller. Cheap and good hotels have excellent service and prices. Youth hostels are a great bargain for student travellers located near the city centre and provide many facilities like internet and cheap drinks at throw away prices.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Air</strong> - Leipzig/Halle Airport sometimes called Schkeuditz Airport is 22 kms northwest of central Leipzig. The airport is the second biggest airport in Eastern Germany after Berlin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train</strong> - Leipzig&#39;s Hauptbahnhof is the largest terminal railway station in Europe with 26 platforms above ground plus 2 tunnel platforms and also includes a large shopping mall, a tedious way to waste away an hour or two between connections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road</strong> - Leipzig can easily be reached by car, as it is very well connected with the Autobahn highway system. The nearest Autobahn highways are A-14, A-9 and A-38.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Several bus companies like FlixBus or MeinFernbus connect Leipzig with other cities in Germany. Long distance buses stop in Leipzig in Goethestrasse lying between Central Station and Opera House and at the airport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - One of the most convenient ways of getting around Leipzig is by car hire one from one of the rental agencies in town. If budget doesn&rsquo;t quite permit luxuries like taxis or car hire, public transport is a good idea. The city has an extensive network of trams, buses and light railways, which cover nearly all of Leipzig and are a fast and economical way of getting around.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - LEIPZIG - {FAMOUS FOR LEIPZIGER ALLERLEI IS A VEGETABLE DISH CONSISTING OF PEAS, CARROTS, ASPARAGUS, MORELS AND CRAYFISH ; LEIPZIGER RABCHEN IS A DESERT MADE FROM &nbsp;PLUMS STUFFED WITH MARZIPAN (IS A TYPE OF CONFECTIONERY CONSISTING &nbsp;SUGAR OR HONEY AND ALMOND) ; LEIPZIGER LERCHE IS A TYPE OF PASTRY FILLED WITH A MIXTURE OF &nbsp;ALMONDS, NUTS, CHERRY}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - ZILLS TUNNEL, LOCATED AT &nbsp;BARFUBGABCHEN 9, 04109 - {FAMOUS FOR BEEF STROGANOFF IS A DISH FILLED WITH BEEF AND SERVED IN A SAUCE WITH SMETANA (SOUR CREAM)}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - RATSKELLER, LOCATED AT LOTTERSTRABE 1, 04109 - (FAMOUS FOR POTATO SOUP)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - CHINABRENNER, LOCATED AT GIE&szlig;ERSTRABE 18, 04229 - (FAMOUS FOR NOODLES AND BEEF DISHES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - MEIN LEIPZIG, LOCATED AT KATHE-KOLLWITZ-STRABE 71, 04109 - (FAMOUS FOR &nbsp;LOBSTER AND FISH DISHES)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(827, 19, 96, 1830, 'Bavaria', 'GERMANY', 'NUREMBERG', 'landscape-1826979_640.jpg', 'landscape-1826979_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">The perfect base point for travellers eager to explore the northern reaches of Bavaria, the historic city of Nuremberg vies with Munich for the top hotspot in the state. And boy does it have some tricks up its sleeve. The onetime epicentre of the Holy Roman Empire, this student packed town comes crowned with the formidable bulwarks and keeps of the Nuremberg Castle and is known widely as one of the hubs of Nazi Germany and also the place of the post war Nuremberg trials. The centre retains a beautiful historic edge too, with half timbered facades and tree dotted cobbled squares, while the beer is top notch famed across Germany for its brooding, dark colour and powerful flavours. Complete with an incredible and tumultuous history, Nuremberg is a 950 year old city with romantic flair, drawing in heritage buffs, foodies and artistic souls alike. This Central European jewel has more than bratwurst and beer. Find cosmopolitan cities, scenic wineries, charming coastline and intriguing history. Germany is a charming European country where history merges with modern excitement. Central Europe&rsquo;s largest country is impressively forward thinking while respecting the past. Rich traditions survive in stunning Alpine ranges and beer flows like water. Picturesque rivers meander through ancient and commercial cities. Sample exquisite wines on the banks of the Rhine, discover the cultural attraction of Berlin, explore the snowy peaks of the Bavarian Alps and enjoy the Baltic coast&rsquo;s scenic seaside. Berlin has fascinating layers of history. Visit ornate and historic museums on Museum Island, pay respects at the Memorial to the Murdered Jews of Europe and stroll along the Spree River&rsquo;s open air East Side Gallery, made from remnants of the Berlin Wall.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />\r\nThe Altstadt and the Egidienviertel districts, the city&#39;s historical sections, provide an array of guest houses and hotels. An alternative is the Gostenhof area, a suburban region with a selection of tourist sites. If staying in Gostenhof, however, one needs to take public transportation to the city centre. For local flair, consider staying in the Knoblauchsland district near the Hauptmarkt. Avoid the Sudstadt district near the train station, which is mainly residential and doesn&#39;t offer many entertainment options or access to sites.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Air </strong>- Nuremberg Airport officially known as Albrecht Durer Airport Nurnberg and getting from the airport to the city is no problem. Air Berlin runs a lot of their flights from Nuremberg. The U2 subway line directly connects Nuremberg Airport with the central train station thus providing access to Nuremberg&#39;s city centre.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train</strong> - Nuremberg Main Station is a regional transportation hub, excellent connections are offered to almost everywhere with ICE service to Munich, Leipzig, Wurzburg, Frankfurt and all major towns along those routes. The main train station itself is located right next to the old city, which is a stroll away.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road</strong> - Nuremberg is connected to the major German Autobahn network through Highways A-3, A-6, A-73 and A-9.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus </strong>- The main bus station is located near the main train station. Eurolines has many connections to Nuremberg from different locations in Europe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Water</strong> - The Port of Nuremberg is located about 6 kms southwest of the old town and Main Railway Station. During the year, over 500 cruise ships stop in Nuremberg.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Nuremberg is one of only four German cities to have an actual U-Bahn and the three line system forms the backbone of public transit in the city. The old town is best explored on foot. To get from one part of the old town to another by car or public transport tourists will often have to leave the old town and re-enter it at a different gate.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - NUREMBERG - {FAMOUS FOR SCH&auml;UFELE IS A DISH MADE FROM PIG&#39;S SHOULDER MEAT ; LEBKUCHEN IS A TYPE OF CAKE MADE FROM HONEY, SPICES LIKE(ANISEED, CORIANDER, CLOVES, GINGER, CARDAMOM), NUTS LIKE (ALMONDS, HAZELNUTS, AND WALNUTS), AND FRUITS ;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - PRISON ST. MICHEL, LOCATED AT &nbsp;IRRERSTRA&szlig;E 2, 90403 - (FAMOUS FOR ONION SOUP)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - HOSERER ROLLY&#39;S, LOCATED AT VORJURASTRA&szlig;E 22, 90453 - (FAMOUS FOR MEAT PATTIES AND CHICKEN WINGS)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n4 - DELPHI, LOCATED AT INNERE LAUFER G. 22, 90403 - (FAMOUS FOR GRILLED OYSTER MUSHROOMS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - RESTAURATION FISCHER, LOCATED AT SCHOTTENGASSE 1, 90402 - (FAMOUS FOR TAGLIATELLE IS A TYPE OF PASTA MADE FROM FLOUR AND EGG WITH MUSSELS)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(828, 19, 96, 1902, 'Baden-Wurttemberg', 'GERMANY', 'HEIDELBERG', 'heidelberg-992560_640.jpg', 'heidelberg-992560_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Heidelberg is an ideal destination for any traveller who wishes to experience the scenic beauty of the lush woodlands, old town architecture and ruined castles of Germany&rsquo;s Rhineland. The city&rsquo;s picturesque location on the Neckar River in southwest Germany has made Heidelberg a top destination for tourists since the 1800s. Praised by poets like Goethe, painted by artists like Turner and rapped by composers like Schumann Heidelberg embodies the spirit of the romantic Rhineland. As the country&rsquo;s oldest university town, it&rsquo;s a surprisingly lively city too, boasting an enticing array of pubs and restaurants that cater to the student population. With historic treasures like the medieval Old Bridge, the Heidelberg Castle, the Church of the Holy Spirit and the Knight St. George House it is no wonder that Heidelberg is one of the top tourist destinations in Germany. The picturesque city suffered little damage during World War-II, with its baroque town centre remaining intact. Home to Germany&rsquo;s oldest university, Heidelberg&rsquo;s long academic history can be retraced along the Philosopher&rsquo;s Walk, a scenic footpath often walked by many earlier philosophers and professors. It&#39;s considered a jewel among German travel destinations. In this region, the legend rich Odenwald a low mountain range opens up toward the sprawling Rhine river plains a densely populated part of the country. Home to the nation&#39;s oldest university, established in 1386, Heidelberg has a huge student population from around Europe. It&#39;s not only a city of academic excellence, but also a place of diversity and youthful energy. Heidelberg has some of the warmest weather Germany has to offer. The city is a popular destination for tourists wanting to enjoy the romantic scenery around the town, discover the history or just go for a pleasant walk along the Neckar River.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">There are many hotels in Heidelberg, so finding a place isn&#39;t that difficult in the off season. Most of the city&#39;s lodging is centralized near Altstadt, the Old Town. Here cafes, shops and tourist sites line the cobbled streets. Many of the guesthouses here work hard to retain the area&#39;s historical feel. Discover the Black Forest, with a luxury stay at an exclusive hotel in Heidelberg from a chic boutique bolthole with spa to a historic inn with wine tasting. Hostels and bed and breakfasts services in Heidelberg make the stay as enjoyable as possible.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />\r\n<strong>By Air</strong> - The closest international airport is Frankfurt Airport in Frankfurt Rhein Main, 80 kms away from Heidelberg and reachable in one hour. &nbsp;It is easily accessible by train, shuttle, rental car or taxi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train</strong> - The main train station, Hauptbahnhof in Heidelberg is centrally located and it has service to both regional towns and major cities, making it easy to get to Heidelberg from anywhere in the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road</strong> - National Highway A-5 connects Heidelberg directly to Frankfurt and Karlsruhe. It&#39;s easy to reach from any direction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Dein Bus offers buses to Heidelberg from Frankfurt, Stuttgart, Cologne and many other cities and tickets can be purchased directly from the driver.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Buses and trams are the main form of transportation in Heidelberg, with the centre hub at Bismarktplatz in Altstadt. Taxis in Heidelberg are available 24 hrs a day and can be found at several main squares. Bicycles are a great way to get around Heidelberg in a short period of time. Heidelberg&rsquo;s mall size makes it an ideal place to explore on foot.</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><br />\r\n<strong>1 - GELATO GO, LOCATED AT HAUPTSTRABE 98-100 - (FAMOUS FOR ICE-CREAM)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - MILDNER&#39;S, LOCATED AT BERGHEIMER STR. 81, 69115 - (FAMOUS FOR COFFEE, SALADS AND CAKES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - LA BOHEME, LOCATED AT STEINGASSE 11 - (FAMOUS FOR SANDWICH)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - ZAFFERANO, LOCATED AT POSTSTRABE 34, 69115 - (FAMOUS FOR PIZZA)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(829, 14, 97, 1904, 'Kanto', 'JAPAN', 'TOKYO', 'boat-1835081_640.jpg', 'boat-1835081_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Tokyo is one of the world&#39;s great cities. It is a hi-tech showcase of modern Japan and yet it still retains the soul of traditional Japan. It manages to be extremely comfortable, even luxurious, while remaining decidedly mysterious and exotic. First and foremost, Tokyo is a food lover&#39;s paradise. Tokyo Metropolis is one of the 47 prefectures of Japan. Tokyo is the capital of Japan, the centre of the Greater Tokyo Area and the largest metropolitan area in the World. It is the seat of the Japanese government and the Imperial Palace and the home of the Japanese Imperial Family. One of the best things to do in Tokyo, especially during spring or autumn, is to take time to sample green tea and Japanese desserts and enjoy maple trees in autumn colours or blooming pink cherry trees in spring. Give rest to aching feet in the small Teahouses serving Green Tea and Japanese Desserts, walk the stepping stones around the pond, enjoy the view of a traditional Japanese Bridge. The city is appealing on many levels and offers everything from quiet gardens to nightlife. It is a city without limits in that a lifetime isn&#39;t long enough to explore everything in town. For example, Tokyo has an estimated 88000 restaurants that would take 120 years to explore at two a day. Nestled in South Eastern Japan, Tokyo boasts not only of towering sky scrapers, immaculate roads and architecture, but also of forests, traditional shrines and cherry blossoms in the spring. A combination of poetic wonder and technological marvel, Tokyo is a must visit for any tourist. The city is not all about slick business suits and traditional kimonos either, it is a thriving pop culture phenomenon for gamers, developers and anime fans alike, with its quirky technological innovations and virtual culture. Tokyo is best perceived as a collection of cities with different characters and vibes, rather than one city alone.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Tokyo abounds with excellent places to stay, from luxury affairs to humble budget friendly lodgings. Its glittering skyscrapers house numerous international four and five star hotels, both in the populous cultural hotspots of Shinjuku and in the business centres of Akasaka and Shinbashi. Meanwhile, hostels catering to the shoestring traveller lie scattered throughout the city. For a memorable, distinctly Japanese experience, seek out a ryokan, a traditional bed and breakfast with tatami floor mats and sliding screen doors. Tokyo has a variety of places to stay in ranging from hostels to five star hotels. One of the unique living arrangements in Tokyo is capsule hotels, which are the cheapest options.&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Tokyo has well established connections to every major city around the world, and every major airline lands at Narita Airport, the most important airport in Tokyo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- From Narita Airport, one can use the road to travel to Tokyo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Tokyo is the centre of railways and the subway in Japan, with connections to every single city in Japan. The subway and the railways can be used with a rechargeable card, but a map is a must as some of the railways and subway lines are slightly difficult to navigate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Tokyo also has a good bus service, for which rechargeable cards are also available. There are intercity buses, as well as intra city bus services. Most intra-city buses require small change, so it is advisable to carry coins and JPY 1000 notes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water </strong>- Waterways are only applicable from island to island in Japan, so from Kyuushu one can take the ferry to Honshu to visit Tokyo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Tokyo has a dense network of railway lines, roads and subways all operated by different companies, under private partnership. This may be of some inconvenience to tourists as each company has a different map for its own territory. Japan&rsquo;s most prominent railways line is the JR Yamanote Line, which connects many cities together, conveniently placing Tokyo at the centre. Prepaid IC cards are the preferred way to get around Tokyo, for every service accepts these cards including cabs and buses.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - TOKYO - {FAMOUS FOR RAMEN IS A TYPE OF NOODLE SOUP MADE FROM &nbsp;WHEAT NOODLES, MEAT OR FISH-BASED BROTH, VEGETABLES ; TEMPURA IS A DISH MADE FROM VEGETABLES, SEAFOOD AND OTHER INGREDIENTS, BATTERED IN EGG AND FLOUR AND THEN FRIED IN VEGETABLE OIL ; SOBA IS A TYPE OF NOODLE MADE FROM &nbsp;BUCKWHEAT FLOUR, AND WHEAT FLOURS AND SERVED WITH EITHER CHILLED &nbsp;SAUCE OR IN HOT BROTH AS A NOODLE SOUP ; UDON IS A TYPE OF NOODLES MADE FROM WHEAT FLOUR, WATER FLAVOURED WITH KAKEJIRU (MADE OF DASHI, SOY SAUCE AND MIRIN) AND TOPPED WITH SCALLIONS ; OKONOMIYAKI IS A TYPE OF PANCAKE MADE FROM CABBAGE ; CHANKONABE IS A TYPE OF STEW MADE FROM DASHI, MIRIN, CHICKEN OR FISH, VEGETABLES (DAIKON, BOK CHOY, AND OTHERS)}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - TORANOMON KOFFEE, LOCATED AT 1 CHOME-1-23 TORANOMON, MINATO, TOKYO - (FAMOUS FOR COFFEE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - BUTAGUMI, LOCATED AT 2 CHOME-24-9 NISHIAZABU, MINATO, TOKYO - (FAMOUS FOR TONKATSU IS A DISH MADE FROM CUTLET (PORK FILLET OR LOIN), CABBAGE AND MISO SOUP)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - ASAKUSA IMAHAN, LOCATED AT 3 CHOME-1-12 NISHIASAKUSA, TAITO - (FAMOUS FOR SUKIYAKI IS A DISH MADE FROM MEAT (BEEF), VEGETABLES, SOY SAUCE, SUGAR AND MIRIN)</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(830, 14, 97, 1905, 'Kansai', 'JAPAN', 'KYOTO', 'gold-temple-420675_640.jpg', 'gold-temple-420675_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">While other cities of Japan embrace modernity without hesitation, Kyoto still maintains traces of tradition and old Japanese culture. With every street, mountain and shrine having something to offer, Kyoto is a must visit for a rich, wholesome cultural experience. The old capital of Japan Kyoto is characterised by its deep interesting cultural roots. Surrounded on three sides by mountains, Kyoto is an incredibly tranquil place filled with more than a thousand temples, vestiges of traditional Japanese culture and gardens that change colours with the seasons. Boasting of picturesque Japanese architecture and traditional geishas, Kyoto also has a diverse range of cuisine, enough to delight the most seasoned connoisseur. Large temples dot the landscape, with every street having something new to offer, like a hidden ramen restaurant or a traditional Japanese dwelling. It is one of the most bicycle friendly cities in Japan, giving plenty of opportunities for tourists to explore Kyoto. Also made for the adventurous, it is home to many hiking trails and exploration sites, in the mountainous regions surrounding it. In conclusion, Kyoto is the best option for the relaxed tourist, who seeks to explore and discover traditional culture and adventure. Kyoto&#39;s architecture it&rsquo;s most famous feature worldwide. Japan&#39;s capital for more than 1000 years, Kyoto was the centre not only of politics, but religion, philosophy, art, culture and cuisine. All of Japan&#39;s refined cultural arts blossomed from seeds planted here including the tea ceremony, Kabuki Theatre, Zen and Tantric Buddhism. Breathtaking sights are everywhere, though some places truly stand out, among them Kyoto&#39;s great temples and the forest cloaked Fushimi Inari Taisha, a shrine pathway through a miles long chain of towering vermilion gates.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Kyoto spoils visitors for choice when it comes to good accommodations, offering everything from traditional ryokans to luxury Western style hotels. In a city used to receiving foreign travellers most establishments know exactly what to offer tourists and how to help newcomers to the area. To avoid paying premium prices during the cherry blossom season consider staying in Osaka located just a 30 minutes train ride away. Centrally located hotels charge more than those in the outer neighbourhoods. Kyoto&rsquo;s accommodation options range from basic guesthouses, youth hostels and temple lodgings to luxurious international hotels and top class ryokan. One night in a full blown Kyoto ryokan enjoying the world&rsquo;s most meticulous service is an experience not to be missed.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The closest airports from Kyoto Kansai and Osaka International Airports have many worldwide airline operations, particularly Air Asia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - By local trains, the one way trip from Tokyo to Kyoto takes about nine hours and typically involves about four transfers of trains.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- Cars can be used, but most of Kyoto&rsquo;s roads are pedestrian and bicycle friendly, so it is recommended to either walk, cycle, or take the bus around Kyoto.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Kyoto boasts of a dense bus network, which seamlessly connects every tourist destination together. Tourists may procure the Kyoto One Day Bus Card or the Kyoto One Day Card that will make bus rides more convenient.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Kyoto has a relatively underdeveloped public transport system, which opens other avenues for citizens to get around this city, walking and cycling. Kyoto is one of the most bicycle friendly areas around Japan and it is recommended, for most of the streets are rectangular and sharp cornered, which renders cabs and buses unable to explore the deeper pockets of Kyoto. However, to travel around the main areas, buses and subways are better, even if they are convoluted and confused.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - KYOTO - {FAMOUS FOR DANGP Is A TYPE OF SWEET MADE FROM RICE FLOUR ; DAIFUKU Is A TYPE OF SWEET MADE FROM AUZKI BEANS CPNSISTING &nbsp;A MOCHI (GLUTINOUS RICE CAKE) STUFFED WITH SWEET FILLING &nbsp;RD BEAN PASTE ; TAIYAKI IS A SNACK MADE FROM BATTER, SWEETENED AZUKI BEANS}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - UDON SANSHIKI, LOCTAED AT 2-9-4 GPJPBASHIHIGASHI, 6-CHPME HIGASHIYAMA-KU, KYOTO - (FAMOUS FOR UDON NOODLES AND CHICKEN TEMPURA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - PREFECTURE, LOCATED AT KYOTO, SHIMPGYO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR KIMCHI IS A SIDE DISH MADE FROM VARIOUS VEGETABLES &nbsp;CABBAGE AND RADISH)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - CAFE BIBLIPTIC HELLO!, LOCTAED AT KYOTO PREFECTURE, KYOTO, NAKAGYO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR PASTRIES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - ARATA, LOCATED AT NIsHIKUJO INMACHI, MINAMI WARD, KYOTO - (FAMOUS FOR OKONOMIYAKI IS A TYPE PF PANCAKE MADE FRPM CABBAGE)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', '');
