(831, 14, 97, 1905, 'Kansai', 'JAPAN', 'OSAKA', 'evening-1736715_640.jpg', 'evening-1736715_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />\r\nOsaka, one of Japan&#39;s largest cities, lies on the south coast of western Honshu at the point where the River Yodo flows into the wide sweep of Osaka Bay, which opens out into the Pacific. The city is bounded on one side by the Kii Peninsula and is shut off from the Inland Sea to the west by the island of Awaji. Its location on the Yodo delta with its network of watercourses and canals spanned by more than a thousand bridges has, deservedly, earned Osaka the nickname &quot;Venice of the East.&quot; While the origins of Osaka date back to the mythological early days of the Japanese Empire, today the city is undoubtedly one of the most modern in Japan, boasting a futuristic skyline along with countless impressive examples of modern architecture. Its world class status is cemented by its many cultural institutions, from its superb museums and art galleries to its ultra modern entertainment, theatre and music venues. Osaka offers visitors a slew of modern as well as historic attractions. It is home to beautiful Osaka Castle, which dates back to 1583 and is one of Japan&rsquo;s most famous landmarks. From Minami&#39;s neon lighted Dotombori and historic Tenno-ji to the high rise class and underground shopping labyrinths of Kita, Osaka is a city that pulses with its own unique rhythm. Though Osaka has no shortage of tourist sites, it is the city itself that is the greatest attraction. Home to some of Japan&#39;s best food, most unique fashions and warmest locals, Osaka does not beg to be explored it demands it. More than anywhere else in Japan, it rewards the impulsive turn down an interesting side street or the chat with a random stranger. People do not come here to see the city, they come to experience it. Osaka&rsquo;s best sights are scattered far and wide, but there are some areas worth exploring on foot. A fine place to start is the castle Osakajo and its immediate environs. Osaka is best enjoyed at night, with its street life, its arcades, gaming centres and small lit up lanes and alleyways.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;">With plenty of accommodation catered to most budgets, Osaka has high end hotels, motels, hostels and rentable apartments. For tourists on a shoestring budget hostels are recommended for they start at very low prices. For tourists wishing to stay at the centre of all activities in Osaka, Minami is the best place to book hotels in. However, for tourists staying temporarily, Kita would be ideal. The majority of Osaka&#39;s moderate and expensive accommodations concentrate in the districts of Umeda, Kyobashi, Namba and Shin Osaka. Base the stay in or near Minami neighbourhood for proximity to a wide selection of shopping and dining options. Many backpackers prefer the budget options in the Tennoji area, where the quality of rooms and prices vary wildly.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Air</strong> - By air, Osaka has limited connectivity compared to other Japanese cities, but is connected by two airports, The Osaka Itami Airport and Kansai International Airport, the latter of which is better connected internationally, while Osaka Itami is better connected domestically.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train</strong> - Japan has a very well connected subway rail system, which connects Osaka to almost every other Japanese city. Subway cards are also operable. However, they are convoluted, so it is advisable to carry a map or an accurate mobile application for navigation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road</strong> - Cars can also be rented, but taxis can be a little bit more on the expensive side.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus </strong>- Osaka has a bus system running within it, and outside it. Bus passes are available, in many denominations. There is also the Osaka One-Day pass which covers all bus travel expenses for a day. However, the subway system is much easier to use.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Water</strong> - Ferries connect Osaka to other islands in Japan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - The subway, the bus and railways are the best modes of transport. 24 hour passes can be procured for heavy travelling, while IC transferable storage cards can be used for payment.</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - OOTAKO, LOCATED AT 1 CHOME-5-10 DOTONBORI, CHUO WARD, OSAKA - {FAMOUS FOR TAKOYAKI IS A TYPE OF SNACK MADE FROM BATTER, OCTOPUS, TEMPURA SCRAPS (TENKASU), GINGER AND ONION}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - AJINOYA, LOCATED AT 1 CHOME-7-16 NANBA, CHUO WARD, OSAKA, OSAKA PREFECTURE - (FAMOUS FOR OKONOMIYAKI IS A TYPE OF PANCAKE MADE FROM FLOUR, WATER, CABBAGE &nbsp;THEN FRIED, ADD SLICES OF PORK OR SEAFOOD LIKE SQUID)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - GOZASOURO,&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;LOCATED AT NISHI-NAKAJIMA, YODOGAWA-KU, OSAKA&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; - (FAMOUS FOR TAIKO-MANJU IS A TYPE OF &nbsp;BAKED SWEET MADE FROM FLOUR, EGGS, AND SUGAR)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - YAEKATSU, LOCATED AT &nbsp;OSAKA PREFECTURE, OSAKA - (FAMOUS FOR KUSHIKATSU IS ADISH MADE FROM CHICKEN, PORK, SEAFOOD, VEGETABLES, EGG, FLOUR AND PANKO)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - TSURUICHI, LOCATED AT 3-3 SHIMOAJIHARACHO, TENNOJI WARD, OSAKA, OSAKA PREFECTURE - (FAMOUS FOR YAKINIKU IS A GRILLED MEAT AND EAT WITH A SAUCE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - KANIDOURAKU, LOCATED AT 1 CHOME-6-18 DOTONBORI, CHUO WARD, OSAKA, OSAKA PREFECTURE - (FAMOUS FOR GRILLED CRABS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>7 - KINGEMON, LOCATED AT 1 CHOME-4-17 DOTONBORI, CHUO WARD, OSAKA, OSAKA PREFECTURE - (FAMOUS FOR RAMEN IS A DISH MADE FROM &nbsp;WHEAT NOODLES, MEAT OR FISH-BASED BROTH, VEGETABLES )</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(832, 14, 97, 1906, 'Chugoku (Sanyo)', 'JAPAN', 'HIROSHIMA', 'hiroshima-1193455_640.jpg', 'hiroshima-1193455_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Hiroshima will always be remembered as the city on which the first atomic bomb was dropped. Although more than 60 percent of the buildings in Hiroshima were destroyed, the city has managed to make an amazing recovery since that devastating August 1945 blast. In fact, by 1974, the city had actually managed to double its pre-war population, and it has also become a popular tourist destination. One of the most popular sites in this city is the Hiroshima Peace Memorial Park, which was created in memory of all those who lost their lives or were injured by the atomic bomb. This large park is home to several interesting sites, including the Peace Memorial Museum where visitors can see the effect the bomb had on the citizens of Hiroshima. Another must see tourist site is the great Torii, a wooden shrine gateway that appears to be floating in the sea at high tide. Travellers can visit two UNESCO World Heritage sites of the Itsukushima Shrine and the Bomb Dome in Peace Memorial Park, learn traditional craftwork at Fudenosato kobo and even explore the lush islands in the Seto Inland Sea. Today, Hiroshima is regarded as the world&#39;s peace capital and is home to such notable attractions as the Hiroshima Peace Institute as well as a number of important structures that survived the bombing, if only as ruins and which provide a sobering reminder of that fateful day. Despite this association, the city remains a vibrant, exciting tourist destination, home to great museums, galleries, and gardens, as well as important cultural events such as the Hiroshima Flower Festival, held each May since 1977 and attracting a million visitors. A tour of Hiroshima is incomplete without a visit to the memorial museum and park that detail and commemorate the horror of the bombing, as well as the flourishing city that had stood prior to it. However, today&#39;s Hiroshima also buzzes with modern cosmopolitanism and commercial success as this coastal city thrives once again. Hiroshima&#39;s attractions include lush landscaped gardens, a burgeoning nightlife and excellent cuisine.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">The majority of places to stay in Hiroshima concentrate in the areas surrounding the train station, the memorial museum and park, and a couple of main boulevards. Here one can find basic, comfortable and clean hostels, dozens of mid range business hotels and a couple of pricier four and five star international chains all of which offer easy access to any of the sights in this compact city. The ordinal hotels serve a western style bed room with some amenities including slippers and nightwear and one may be able to have breakfast for free in according to the accommodation plans. For an adventurous and very affordable overnight stay in Hiroshima, tourists can even sleep in private pods attached to the train station&#39;s south side.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Hiroshima Airport connects to domestic destinations in Japan. Both ANA and JAL offer flights from Tokyo Haneda and Sapporo Chitose airports. There are direct international flights from Beijing, Dalian, Hongkong, Shanghai, Seoul and Taipei.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - JR Hiroshima Station at 25 minute walk from the Peace Park is a major station on the JR West Sanyo Shinkansen line. It is roughly 40 minutes from Okayama and 90 minutes from Shin Osaka. Tokyo is four hours away via Nozomi and five hours via Hikari.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Hiroshima Bus Centre is on the third floor of the SOGO department store, which is just down the street from the Peace Park. Long distance buses arrive and depart from the north exit of JR Hiroshima Station, where there is a JR Bus counter and the Hiroshima Bus Centre in the city centre. There is service to and from cities in Kanto, Kansai, Kyushu, Shikoku and much of the rest of Japan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Heading southwest on National Highway Route 54 will take tourists to the centre of town. Route 2 is the major east/west artery, south of the city centre.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water</strong> - Ferries dock at Hiroshima&#39;s Ujina Port, which also serves as terminus for several tram lines. Ishizaki Kisen operates daily service to and from Matsuyama in Shikoku, with some boats stopping in Kure along the way. The ride takes 70 to 80 minutes to reach Matsuyama.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Hiroshima has an extensive tram network, which is operated by Hiroden. It&#39;s a slow but reliable way of getting around. Bus lines run through Hiroshima and out to the suburbs. The modern Astram links the city centre with the northern suburbs, although there aren&#39;t many tourist sites out that way. Hiroshima is great city for cycling and most of the sidewalks are fairly wide by Japanese standards.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - KAKIYA, LOCATED AT 539 MIYAJIMACHO, HIROSHIMA PREFECTURE - (FAMOUS FOR OYSTERS IS A SEAFOOD)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - BAKUDANYA, LOCATED AT 2-12 SHINTENCHI, NAKA WARD, HIROSHIMA, HIROSHIMA PREFECTURE - (FAMOUS FOR TSUKEMEN IS A TYPE OF NOODLE SOUP MADE FROM &nbsp;COLD RAMEN NOODLES, BROTH)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - OKONOMI-MURA, LOCATED AT 5-13 SHINTENCHI, NAKA-KU, HIROSHIMA - (FAMOUS FOR JAPANESE PANCAKE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - SHANTI VEGAN CAFE, LOCATED AT 2F MONDANO BUILDING, 2-20 MIKAWA-CHO, NAKA-KU, HIROSHIMA - (FAMOUS FOR SPRINGS ROLLS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - YAKIGAKI-NO-HAYASHI, LOCATED AT 505-1, HATSUKAICHI, HIROSHIMA - (FAMOUS FOR FRIED PORK)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n6 - POLAR BEAR, LOCATED AT 5-2 NAKA-KU TATEMACHI, HIROSHIMA, JAPAN - (FAMOUS FOR SANDWICH)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>7 - ZONA ITALY, LOCATED AT FURUTADAI, NISHI-KU, HIROSHIMA, JAPAN - (FAMOUS FOR PIZZA)</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(833, 14, 97, 1907, 'Chubu (Tokai)', 'JAPAN', 'NAGOYA', 'nagoya-1697559_640.jpg', 'nagoya-1697559_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">In 1612, shogun Ieyasu Tokugawa established Nagoya by permitting his ninth son to build a castle here. Industry and merchant houses sprang up in the shadow of this magnificent fortress, as did pleasure quarters for samurai. Supported by taxing the rich harvests of the surrounding Nobi plain, the Tokugawa family used the castle as its power centre for the next 250 years. After the Meiji Restoration in 1868, when Japan began trade with the West in earnest, Nagoya developed rapidly. When the harbour opened to international shipping in 1907, Nagoya&#39;s industrial growth accelerated, and by the 1930s it was supporting Japanese expansionism in China with munitions and aircraft. This choice of industry was Nagoya&#39;s downfall very little of the city was left standing after World War II. Thanks to its position opening onto the Pacific, Nagoya has developed into the country&#39;s busiest port and has long been an important manufacturing site of such traditional industries as ceramics and textiles. The ceramics industry was established here in the 12th century and has become somewhat of a tourist attraction thanks to its numerous workshops and factory tours. Many of the city&#39;s historic sites remain, including its 16th century castle which like much of the city centre was rebuilt after the destruction of WW-II. These days, this large city is a pleasure to visit for its excellent network of wide modern streets, museums, art galleries and historic temples. Nagoya is a city which was known in the past for its samurai and ninja culture but has fast evolved to become the hub of automobile and aircraft manufacturing in Japan. Slowly it is making its way onto the tourist map as well for those who want to get away from the city madness in Tokyo and enjoy a slightly off beaten vacation in Japan. Less overwhelming than Tokyo or Osaka, the capital of Aichi ken and Japan&rsquo;s fourth largest city provides an easily accessible introduction to urban Japan and all its contemporary delights, one of the highlights of which is its food scene.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Nagoya has many options for inbound tourists from the high end hotels like to the small and cosy hotels. Guest houses, hostels and capsule inns are popular among those looking for budget accommodations. Finding a place to stay in Nagoya is not going to be difficult for a first time traveller. The central district, just south from the castle and its gardens, houses the bulk of accommodations in Nagoya. One will find a good range of standard hotels with onsite restaurants simple rooms and perhaps a pool in this area. Look slightly to the west or closer to the castle to find more luxurious accommodations.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The Chubu Centrair International Airport is only 30 minutes away from the centre of the island. It is well connected by the Meitetsu Airport Line. The faster trains run every half an hour along with the slower limited express trains as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Car rentals in Nagoya are very common. Toyota offers the most secure and hassle free car rental service. English speaking service is also provided to customers since it is a multi-national company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Located on the Tokaido Shinkansen route, Nagoya is an important station between Tokyo and Osaka. There are various other trains which ply to and from other cities to Nagoya depending on the subway line and frequency. Check local train route for the best way to commute while changing minimum number of stops.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Regular buses ply to and fro Nagoya from other cities in Japan. Travellers have the option of landing in Tokyo and reaching Nagoya in 6 to 9 hours by bus instead of taking the train.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - The local train system is the best way to get around the city. Japan has six subway lines and the most famous of them, the JR Tokaido Shinkansen, connects Tokyo and Nagoya. Nozomi, Hikari and Kodama are high speed trains and the Japan Rail pass can be made for the Hikari or the Kodama trains. Apart from that highway buses and local trains ply on a regular interval too.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align:center"><strong>1 - NAGOYA - {FAMOUS FOR TEBASAKI IS A DISH MADE WITH BONE-IN CHICKEN WINGS ; HITSUMABUSHI IS A DISH MADE FROM RICE, GRILLED UNAGI EEL, PEPPER POWDER, NORI SEAWEED, ONIONS, WASABI PASTE AND DASHI ; MISO UDON NOODLE SOUP (MISO NIKOMI UDON) IS A STAPLE MADE FROM UDON NOODLES, MISO (SOY BEAN PASTE, SAKE, SUGAR, CHICKEN, KAMABOKO (FISH CAKE), ABURAAGE (DEEP-FRIED TOFU), NEGI(ONIONS), EGG AND CHILLI POWDER ; TENMUSU IS A DISH IN JAPANESE CUISINE THAT CONSISTS OF A RICE BALL WRAPPED WITH NORI (DRIED RED ALGAE)}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:center"><strong>2 - MISOKATSU YABATON HONTEN, LOCATED AT 3 CHOME-6-18 OSU, NAKA WARD, NAGOYA, AICHI PREFECTURE - (FAMOUS FOR MISO KATSU IS A DISH, WHICH IS DEEP FRIED PORK CUTLETS SERVED WITH &nbsp;CABBAGE AND RICE)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(834, 14, 97, 1904, 'Kanto', 'JAPAN', 'KAMAKURA', 'big-buddha-956449_640.jpg', 'big-buddha-956449_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">An hour&rsquo;s train ride south of Tokyo lays the small, relaxed town of Kamakura, trapped between the sea and a circle of wooded hills. The town is steeped in history, and many of its 65 temples and 19 shrines date back some eight centuries, when, for a brief and tumultuous period, it was Japan&rsquo;s political and military centre. It&rsquo;s most famous sight is the Daibutsu, a glorious bronze Buddha surrounded by trees, but the town&rsquo;s ancient Zen temples are equally compelling. Kamakura is also well known for its spring blossoms and autumn colours and many temple gardens are famous for a particular flower Japanese apricot at Zuisen-ji, Tokei-ji and hydrangea at Meigetsu. Kamakura&rsquo;s prime sights can be covered on a day trip from Tokyo, but the town more than justifies a two day visit, allowing time to explore the enchanting temples of east Kamakura, to follow one of the gentle hiking courses up into the hills or to ride the Enoden line a few kilometres west to tiny Enoshima Island. In summer, the coast here is a favourite spot for windsurfing. As a religious centre, Kamakura presents an extraordinary legacy. Most of its temples and shrines are in settings of remarkable beauty many are designated National Treasures. To increase the chances of seeing Kamakura at its best, avoid coming at the weekend. The rest of the time this seaside town basks in distinctly serene atmosphere exuded by over 60 religious edifices. Kamakura, both the homeland of Zen Buddhism and firm friend of surfers, has somehow managed to reconcile such apparently contradictory facets. Nestled between the beaches and wooded hills, hedonism and meditation co-exist in this town that was the capital of Japan from 1192 for almost two centuries.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Given the easy access from Tokyo via a number of public transport options, the vast majority of visitors to Kamakura choose to stay in the capital and head here for a day trip. If it feels there&#39;s too much to see in one day, then one will be pleased to find a decent selection of accommodations in Kamakura itself. Down by the sea sit perhaps the most luxurious of the crop, with sea views high on the list of desires for those who stay here. Follow the river as it snakes inland past the train station and see a good number of more standard hotels, as well as particularly budget friendly guesthouses.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Narita Airport is 123 kms northeast of Kamakura. Some trains offer direct service to Kamakura station, otherwise change at wherever the train terminates to the next train bound for Zushi, Yokosuka or Kurihama.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - The fastest way to Kamakura Station is by JR Yokosuka Line from Tokyo Station or Yokohama. The JR Kamakura Enoshima Pass gets a round trip in this area with unlimited use of JR, Enoden and Shonan Monorail lines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Kamakura is just a little too big to cover on foot, but a network of buses radiates out from the train station. For the energetic ones, there is a nice hike starting from Jochiiji temple and ending near the Kotokuin. One will walk, with some climbing, through forest. Bicycles can be rented from several locations, though rates are expensive.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - LATTERIA BEBE KAMAKURA, LOCATED AT KANAGAWA PREFECTURE, KAMAKURA - (FAMOUS FOR &nbsp;PIZZA AND PASTA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - GARDEN HOUSE, LOCATED AT 15-46 ONARIMACHI, KAMAKURA - (FAMOUS FOR PANCAKES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - RANS, LOCATED AT 1 CHOME&minus;5&minus;38, YUKINOSHITA - (FAMOUS FOR FOCACCIA IS A TYPE OF FLATBREAD MADE FROM FLOUR, OIL, WATER, SALT AND YEAST)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - MERCER CAFE, LOCATED AT 2 CHOME-6-28 KOMACHI, KAMAKURA - (FAMOUS FOR SPICY CHICKEN SALAD, SALMON TARTAR AND FRENCH TOAST)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - KATSURETSU-AN, LOCATED AT 12-10 ONARIMACHI, KAMAKURA - (FAMOUS FOR TONKATSU IS A DISH MADE FROM CUTLET (PORK FILLET OR LOIN), CABBAGE AND MISO SOUP)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - CARAWAY, LOCATED AT 2 CHOME-12-20 KOMACHI, KAMAKURA-SHI - (FAMOUS FOR CHICKEN CURRY)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>7 - GOOD MELLOWS, LOCATED AT 27-39 SAKANOSHITA, KAMAKURA - (FAMOUS FOR BURGER)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>8 - KEBAB KAMAKURA, LOCATED AT 1 CHOME-16 HASE, KAMAKURA - (FAMOUS FOR KEBABS AND ICE CREAM)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>9 - OCEAN HARVEST COCOMO, LOCATED AT 2 &nbsp;CHOME-8-8 HASE, KAMAKURA-SHI - (FAMOUS FOR &nbsp;SEAFOOD DISHES)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n10 - KUAAINA, LOCATED AT 4-3-9 YUIGAHAMA, KAMAKURA - (FAMOUS FOR &nbsp;BURGERS AND SANDWICHES)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(835, 14, 97, 1905, 'Kansai', 'JAPAN', 'UJI', 'byodo-in-1026870_640.jpg', 'byodo-in-1026870_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Uji is a popular city in southern Kyoto Prefecture, especially famous for its Byodoin Temple. Featuring two UNESCO World Heritage sites, the town is often overlooked by first time visitors to Japan in favour of Kyoto and Nara. Uji is surrounded by forested hills with Uji River passing through the city. Uji was established in the 4th century by the semi mythical Emperor Ojin, who is said to have built a palace here. The city really came into prominence when Shogun Ashikaga Yoshimitsu heavily promoted tea cultivation and production in the area during his 1358-1408 reigns. The area has since been well known for its superior taste and has some of the oldest tea shops in Japan. The first place to see has got to be Byodoin Temple, a Buddhist temple originally built over one thousand years ago in 998. Byodoin is one of the UNESCO World Heritage sites in Uji. The stunning temple, surrounded by a pond and with extremely distinct architectural touches, is in another league compared to most temples in Japan. Another UNESCO World Heritage site is Ujigami Shrine. This small but interesting shrine is said to be the oldest Shinto shrine in the world. It is a short walk across Uji River&#39;s red Japanese bridges and at the bottom of Daikichiyamafuchi Park. Those looking for a short hike can continue up the mountain to the park&#39;s summit for a view over Uji. Uji is also famous for its green tea. While Kozanji Temple in Kyoto is believed to be the original site of tea cultivation in Japan, Uji&#39;s tea became better known for its superior quality in the 1100s. Uji is the premier green tea manufacturing location in Japan, and visitors will see the name in shops and cafes all across the nation. The establishments in Uji offer not just traditional tea experiences, but everything from green tea ice cream to green tea biscuits. The Tale of Genji Museum is also worth visiting nearby for those interested in the story. A little out of the centre by bus is Mimurotoji Temple which is known for its expansive gardens. Mimurotoji draws the crowds for to its cherry blossoms in spring, azaleas in May, hydrangeas in June and lotus flowers in July and August.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">The small and historical city of Uji has a modest collection of accommodations, but many of them provide an atmospheric stay. Traditional ryokan represent some of the most authentic and memorable places to stay here, with the most popular ones sitting on the western bank of the river. Elsewhere, a couple of simple hotels sit next to the main train station. The vast majority of visitors to Uji opt to stay in either Kyoto or Nara, with both accessible in under an hour by road and rail.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The nearest airport from Uji is Kansai International Airport in Osaka.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Kyoto city and Uji are connected by frequent trains along the JR Nara Line. Osaka and Uji are connected by frequent trains along the Keihan Line. Uji is on the JR Nara Line. From Kyoto Station, it takes about 17 minutes via rapid train or about 27 minutes via local.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Most of the sights are a short walk from JR Uji station or, on the other side of the river, Keihan Uji station. It&#39;s possible to sketch out an itinerary covering all of the major sights in a day, but an unplanned stroll along either side of the Uji River is likely to be just as rewarding.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - GOCHIO CAF&Eacute;, LOCATED AT 63 UJI ICHIBAN, UJI, KYOTO - (FAMOUS FOR PASTA AND FRENCH TOAST)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - MASUDA CHAHO, LOCATED AT 21-3 UJI RENGE, UJI, KYOTO - (FAMOUS FOR ICE-CREAM)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - CHAGANJU CAF&Eacute;, LOCATED AT ICHIBAN-66-1 UJI, KYOTO PREFECTURE - (FAMOUS FOR CREPE IS A TPE OF PANCAKE MADE FROM WHEAT FLOUR OR BUCKWHEAT FLOUR, MILK AND EGGS)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(836, 14, 97, 1908, 'Hokkaido', 'JAPAN', 'SAPPORO', 'japan-2504799_640.jpg', 'japan-2504799_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Home to the 1972 Winter Olympics and Japan&#39;s most succulent crab, tasty noodles and refreshing beer, Hokkaido&#39;s northern metropolis beckons visitors to its wide boulevards, challenging ski slopes and boundless opportunities for business development. The largest city on Japan&#39;s northernmost island of Hokkaido Sapporo offers many great reasons to visit. Although travel to this largely hilly region only became fashionable after it hosted the 1972 Winter Olympics, the city is more than making up for it now with events such as the famous Sapporo Snow Festival, one of Japan&#39;s largest winter events attracting more than two million visitors every winter. In addition, the city regularly hosts important international sporting events as well as major political gatherings such as G8 Summits. Sapporo also plays a role as a major cultural destination and is home to some of Japan&#39;s best known culinary dishes, theatrical and musical events, as well as museums and lovely parks well worth including on your Japanese itinerary. Sapporo, located in the mountains and renowned for its cold brew, is one of the best places to visit in Japan for thrill seekers and adventure travellers. Sapporo hosts ice sculpture festivals, ski and snowboard competitions and is a prime base for athletes wanting to hit the slopes themselves. Sapporo&#39;s streets form a perfect grid pattern, which leaves plenty of room for green spaces, hence the large number of parks and gardens. In winter, when the city is carpeted with snow, life moves underground for the most part. All year round, Japan&#39;s fifth largest city boasts a lively night life. Other events happen annually in Sapporo, including a summer beer festival and a lilac celebration in the spring. Although relatively new and not known for its historic attractions, the city&#39;s broad tree lined boulevards, lush parks, ski resorts and vibrant nightlife make up for its lack of heritage. A Sapporo itinerary should include its famous beer gardens, landmark buildings and local delicacies such as miso ramen and white sweethearts, a type of chocolate biscuit.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Most of the hotels in Sapporo are centrally located and within walking distance of many of the local tourist attractions and restaurants, as well as being generally more affordable than those in Tokyo, Osaka and Kyoto. Tourists will find a few options in Minami-ku, but the areas of Chuo-ku around the centrally located Odori Park and busy red light district of Susukino are definitely the most preferable and have the most options. Tourists will be able to choose from a variety of accommodation options for your stay in Sapporo, including opulent and upscale hotels. Mid range and high end establishments line the streets of the city centre while options for the budget conscious traveller are hostels, guesthouses and campsites, open from May to November.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The New Chitose Airport is located approximately 40.2 kms outside Sapporo and offers service to destinations around the globe. Several airlines like Nippon Airways, Cathay Pacific, China Eastern Airlines, etc. offer transportation to the New Chitose Airport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Sapporo is serviced by JR Hokkaido which offers a number of local and express services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - JR Hokkaido Bus offers transportation to destinations throughout Japan. Hokkaido Chuo Bus and Jotetsu Bus also provide transportation to local and national destinations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- Sapporo is accessible by Route 36. Driving conditions during winter months are often hazardous, so car rental is not advisable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around </strong>- Sapporo is serviced by a comprehensive system of public transit options. The city&#39;s three subway lines Tozaisen, Nanpokusen and Tohosen offer highly efficient service. Bus transit is available on Shiei Bus. From the end of April to the beginning of November the Sapporo Lincle Bus provides a bus tour of the city.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1- NISHITONDENDORI SOUP CURRY, LOCATED AT 13 CHOME-4-5 MINAMI 8 JONISHI, CHUO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR TOMATO CHEESE CURRY)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - SAPPORO KANI HONKE SUSUKINO, LOCATED AT 4 CHOME-1-3 MINAMI 6 JONISHI, CHUO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR CRAB CAKE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - DARUMA, LOCATED AT &nbsp;4 CHOME, JONISHI, &nbsp;6 MINAMI, CHUO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR GRILLED MUTTON BARBECUE SERVED WITH ONIONS)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - SAPPORO RAMEN REPUBLIC, LOCATED AT 2 CHOME, JONISHI &nbsp;5 KITA, CHUO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR RAMEN IS A DISH MADE FROM WHEAT NOODLES, MEAT OR FISH-BASED BROTH, AND VEGETABLES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - TONKATSU TAMAFUJI, LOCATED AT 2 CHOME-1 KITA 5 JONISHI, CHUO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR FRIED PORK)</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(837, 14, 97, 1904, 'Kanto', 'JAPAN', 'YOKOHAMA', 'japan-2379070_640.jpg', 'japan-2379070_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">On its southern borders Tokyo merges with Yokohama, Japan&rsquo;s second most populous city and a major international port. Yokohama feels far more spacious and airy than the capital, thanks to its open harbour frontage and generally low rise skyline and though it can&rsquo;t claim any outstanding sights, the place has enough of interest to justify day&rsquo;s outing from Tokyo. Locals are proud of their city&rsquo;s international heritage and there&rsquo;s definitely a cosmopolitan flavour to the place, with its scattering of Western style buildings, Chinese temples and world cuisines and its sizeable foreign community. It might seem strange to come all this way to look at 19th century European style architecture, but the upmarket suburb of Yamate is one of the city&rsquo;s highlights, an area of handsome residences, church spires and bijou teashops. Yamate&rsquo;s exotic attractions still draw Japanese tourists in large numbers, as do the vibrant alleys and speciality restaurants of nearby Chinatown. There&rsquo;s a clutch of assorted museums along the seafront and north to where Kannai boasts a few grand old Western edifices, in complete contrast to the Minato Mirai 21 development&rsquo;s hi-tech skyscrapers in the distance. A century and a half ago Yokohama consisted of just a few fishermen&#39;s shacks on the banks of Tokyo Bay, 30 kms south of the capital. The sleepy village of 600 inhabitants was roused by the trade treaty between the US and Japan in 1850 and transformed into a major commercial port, going on to become Japan&#39;s second biggest city. This cosmopolitan hub has a Chinatown, European districts and a dazzling seafront development, Minato Mirai 21, which has its sights firmly set on the future. Japan&#39;s largest port city, Yokohama is an internationally minded community of splendid parks, thriving industry, sumptuous cuisine and a singular history. From age old Chinatown to futuristic Minato Mirai 21 one will savour this ever friendly city.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><br />\r\nAlthough Yokohama is often thought of primarily as a residential city, it offers a wealth of fine accommodations for both tourists and business travellers alike with rooms priced to suit all types and budget requirements. Global travellers who require budget lodgings are in luck when visiting Yokohama. Unlike in more expensive cities, there are numerous places where one can enjoy a very comfortable stay for very less price. Tourists can find plenty of budgets friendly accommodation options, such as dormitory style hostels, clustered around the Ishikawa-cho and Sakuragi-cho train stations, offering easy access to some of Yokohama&#39;s best known attractions. If looking to spend more, the Minato Mirai district boasts a few luxurious, high end hotels.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Yokohama is accessible by train from Narita International Airport. There are a number of transit services that provide transportation from Narita International Airport to Yokohama and destinations throughout Japan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Rail services are provided by JR East, Keikyu Railway and Sagami Railway. Train lines include the Tokyu Toyoko Line, the JR Tokaido Line, the JR Yokosuka Line, the JR Shinjuku Line, the JR Keihin-Tohoku Line, the Jr Tokaido Shinkansen and the Keikyu Keihin kyuko Line.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - JR Highway buses offer service to destinations throughout Japan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Yokohama is accessible by the Shuto Kosok Yokokhane Expressway, the Shuto Kosoku Wangan Expressway, the Daisan Keihin Expressway, the Tokyo Aqua Line and the Shuto Kosoku Wangan Expressway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Yokohama is easily travelled by their local metro line and extensive bus network. A sea bus operates between JR Yokohama station, Minato Mirai and Yamashita Park and is one of the nicest ways to get around on a sunny day. Akai Kutsu Bus is a sightseeing bus around Minatomirai, Chinatown and Motomachi. Central Yokohama is comparatively compact and the Chinatown Park area is best explored on foot.</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - EDOSEI, LOCATED AT YAMASHITACHO, NAKA WARD, YOKOHAMA - (FAMOUS FOR NIKUMAN IS A SNACK FOOD MADE FROM DOUGH, GROUND PORK OR BEEF)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - POMPADOUR, LOCATED AT 2 CHOME-3-4 MINATOMIRAI, NISHI WARD - (FAMOUS FOR CURRY DOUGHNUTS IS A SNACK MADE FROM FLOUR, DRY YEAST, POWDERED MILK, SALT, MARGARINE, EGG AND SUGAR FILLED WITH ONION, POTATOES, CHICKEN, CURRY POWDER)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - SEIHURO, LOCATED AT 190 YAMASHITA-CHO, NAKA-KU - (FAMOUS FOR SHUMAI IS A TYPE OF DUMPLING PORK, SHRIMP, CHINESE BLACK MUSHROOM, LYE WATER DOUGH)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - LA MERE POULARD, LOCATED AT 3-5-1 MINATOMIRAI, NISHI-KU, YOKOHAMA - (FAMOUS FOR OMURICE IS A DISH CONSISTING OF AN OMELETTE MADE WITH FRIED RICE AND &nbsp;TOPPED WITH KETCHUP)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - NANJYA MONJYA CAF&Eacute;, LOCATED AT 5-55 MITSUZAWA HIGASHIMACHI, KANAGAWA WARD - (FAMOUS FOR FRENCH TOAST)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - BILLS RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT 1-2 SHINKO, NAKA-KU - (FAMOUS FOR PANCAKE)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(838, 14, 97, 1909, 'Kyushu', 'JAPAN', 'FUKUOKA', 'japan-2415132_640.jpg', 'japan-2415132_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">One of Japan&#39;s largest cities, Fukuoka is the administrative, economic and cultural centre of the southernmost Island of Kyushu and is one of the country&#39;s most progressive cities. Located in Hakata Bay, Fukuoka is divided in two by the River Naka, with Hakata, the older eastern part of the city, serving as an important port and commercial centre. The once fortified town of Fukuoka grew in importance during the 17th century and after amalgamation with Hakata in 1889 became an important cultural centre. These days, Fukuoka is home to numerous fine museums, art galleries and theatres, as well as sporting events and festivals, most notably the famous Hakata Gion Yamakasa a two week long, 700 year old celebration held each July that involves colourful parades, traditional races and costumes, along with musical offerings. Fukuoka also offers many interesting shopping opportunities, in particular in Canal City Hakata, a city within a city complete with a waterway running through a complex of hotels, restaurants, arcades, cinemas and a theatre. The largest city on the island, Fukuoka formed through the merger of two former cities that had grown up either side of the Naka River. Tracing its history as a trading port settlement back around 2000 years, a complex narrative of cultural exchange, feudal fighting, and regional trade has left the city with a number of interesting historical sites and folk traditions, which one can discover at a wealth of museums across the city. Fukuoka, to the north of Kyushu Island, is a dynamic city. It has its sights firmly set on the future, as illustrated by the ultra modern architecture in the Momochi district and an economy based on new technologies as well as the fantastic Asian Art Museum. But the city has a 2000 year history that has been deeply influenced by its proximity to China and Korea. Its old town is still intact and the shops are now concentrated there. Behold a shining coastal city, crackling with youthful energy. Discover smiling crowds, lush mountains, sunny beaches, spacious avenues and lively arcades, where Hakata merchants have peddled for centuries. Fukuoka is the centre of Kyushu culture and commerce.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">As the largest city on the island, a hub of commerce, transport and tourism and a base for exploration of the wider region, Fukuoka offers plenty of accommodations to choose from. The most established hotels lie in Chuo Ward, the district closest to the port and on the western bank of the Naka River. Standard and luxury options abound in the area and surrounding districts, offering a range of additional facilities to suit all tastes and budgets. Budget conscious travellers will be pleased to find hostels and guest houses throughout the city, but again, primarily in this central area.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The Fukuoka Airport is Fukuoka&#39;s major airport. Within the country, Japan Airlines and ANA fly to Fukuoka from larger cities including Tokyo, Osaka and Nagoya.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Hakata Station is the terminus of the Sanyo Shinkansen and Kyushu Shinkansen. Sanyo Shinkansen services are offered from Kokura in Kitakyushu, Shimonoseki, Hiroshima, Okayama and Osaka and through via the Tokaido Shinkansen from Kyoto, Nagoya and Tokyo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Many overnight bus services run into Fukuoka from other parts of the country. The Moonlight overnight bus runs from Osaka Umeda to Fukuoka, the Kyoto overnight bus runs from Kyoto to Fukuoka and the oddly named Dontaku runs from Nagoya to Fukuoka.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water</strong> - JR Kyushu&#39;s Jet Ferry the Beetle hydrofoils to Busan. It runs five times a day. They are quick, but in 2005 one hit a whale and had to be towed back to Busan. Since then, the JR Kyushu Jet Ferry Inc. plays sounds that whales dislike using speakers to avoid further accidents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Fukuoka is served by 3 subway lines. The Hakata subway station, located under the JR Hakata Station, can take passengers straight to Fukuoka International Airport, as well as to Tenjin, the city&#39;s downtown district and other major stops. Fukuoka is well served by Nishitetsu buses. Taxis are ubiquitous in the central part of the city as well as main thoroughfares. Bicycle is probably the best way to get around.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - ICHIRAN, LOCATED AT 5 CHOME-3-2 NAKASU, HAKATA WARD - (FAMOUS FOR RAMEN IS A DISH MADE FROM WHEAT NOODLES, MEAT OR FISH-BASED BROTH, VEGETABLES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - HAKATA MOTSUNABE HAKKEI, LOCATED AT 8-164, KAMISHIROUZU, KASUGA-CITY - (FAMOUS FOR MOTSUNABE IS A SOUP DISH MADE FROM MISO, OR SOY SAUCE, GARLIC, CHILI PEPPER, BEEF OR PORK OFFAL, CHAMPON)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - RESTAURANT HAKATA HIRAMATSU, LOCATED AT 3-1 SHIMOKAWABATAMACHI, HAKATA WARD - (FAMOUS FOR FOIE GRAS IS A FOOD MADE FROM LIVER OF DUCK WRAPPED IN SAVOY CABBAGE LEAVES, SERVED WITH A FRAGRANT SAUCE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - YAMANAKA SUSHI, LOCATED AT 2 CHOME-8-8 WATANABEDORI, CHUO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR SEA FOOD)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - RISTORANTE ASO TENJIN, LOCATED AT &nbsp;2 CHOME&minus;5, TENJIN, &nbsp;CHUO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR SPAGHETTI ALLA PUTTANESCA IS A TPE OF PASTA DISH &nbsp;MADE FROM SPAGHETTI ( MADE FROM SEMOLINA OR FLOUR, WATER), TOMATOES, OLIVES, CAPERS, GARLIC AND ANCHOVIES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - YAKITORI DAISHIZEN, LOCATED AT 9-4 NISHINAKASU, CHUO WARD - (FAMOUS FOR HORSE MEAT)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>7 - HAKATA MIZUTAKI TORIDEN, LOCATED IN FUKUOKA - (FAMOUS FOR MIZUTAKI IS A TYPE OF HOT POT DISH MADE FROM FISH OR &nbsp;MEAT AND VEGETABLES AND DIPPED IN PONZU SAUCE WITH CHICKEN SOUP)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(839, 14, 97, 1905, 'Kansai', 'JAPAN', 'HIMEJI', 'himeji-1207394_640.jpg', 'himeji-1207394_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">This modern town 50 kms to the west of Kobe is worth a stay for its recently restored feudal castle, considered to be the finest of Japan. The castle grounds are home to the lovely Koukoen Japanese gardens and Fine Arts, History of the Prefecture and Literature museums. Between Himeji Station and the castle, Miyuki Street is packed tight with shops, souvenir boutiques and restaurants, all of which are crammed at the weekends. The castle around which the city of Himeji has developed represents one of the best preserved in the country, and has been designated as a national treasure and a World Heritage Site. Other landmarks of the feudal age in Himeji include traditional samurai districts, with the renovated homes and artfully arranged gardens adding to the historical core of the city, and a number of museums explaining their history, importance and relevance to contemporary Japanese culture. With half a million inhabitants, Himeji is the second largest city of Hyogo Prefecture after Kobe. It can be reached in less than one hour from Osaka or Kyoto and is also a popular stopover on journeys along the Sanyo Shinkansen. There&rsquo;s something very relaxing about walking the streets of Himeji. A relatively small town, Himeji exudes relaxation as locals to this town are chilled and laid back individuals themselves. In spite of this, Himeji is home to some exciting attractions that could turn a regular vacation into an extraordinary one. The castle hosts the Himeji Castle Cherry Blossom Viewing Fair, cherry blossom viewing drum music performance and Princess Senhime Peony Festival in spring, Himeji Castle Festival in summer, Moon Viewing Fair and Himeji Ceramics Market in autumn. Visitors can enjoy the city throughout the year.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">The UNESCO protected castle brings plenty of visitors to Himeji, so the quiet city possesses enough accommodations to be able to suit their eclectic tastes and diverse budgets. Located in clusters among the main commercial squares close to the train station tourists will find the main hotels, including budget and luxury options. Look to the side streets of this central district for a fair selection of hostels and guesthouses. The high speed train service connecting Himeji to Osaka and Kyoto means that many visitors choose to visit during a day trip from one of these large cities.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The nearest airport from Himeji city is Kobe Airport. There are regular flights to and from Kobe to major cites of the country and other coutries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- Tokyo and Himeji are connected with each other by the JR Tokaido/Sanyo Shinkansen. Nozomi trains require about 3 hours reaching Himeji Station from Tokyo, while direct Hikari trains require roughly 3.5 hours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Shinki Bus and Keio Bus operate night buses between Himeji Station and Tokyo&rsquo;s Shinjuku Bus Terminal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around </strong>- The broad Otemae dori Street leads straight from JR Himeji Station to Himeji Castle. Tourists can walk from the station to the castle&#39;s entrance gate in about 15 to 20 minutes. Himeji is also covered by a dense bus network that is operated by Shinki Bus. Its main bus terminal is in front of JR Himeji Station.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - GASSAI, LOCATED AT 161 TOYOZAWACHO - (FAMOUS FOR FISH CAKES WITH CHEESE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - CAFE LAMP, LOCATED AT 68 HONMACHI - (FAMOUS FOR PASTRIES, PIZZAS, AND SANDWICHES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - KOBA&amp;MORE, LOCATED AT 59, GOFUKUMACHI - (FAMOUS FOR RAMEN IS A DISH MADE FROM WHEAT NOODLES, MEAT OR FISH-BASED BROTH, VEGETABLES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - BAOBAB, LOCATED AT 78 KONYAMACHI, OMIZOSUJI SHOPPING STREET - (FAMOUS FOR INDIAN CURRIES WITH NAN)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - FUKUTEI, LOCATED AT &nbsp;KAMEIMACHI - (FAMOUS FOR GRILLED FISH)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - TAKOPIA, LOCATED IN HIMEJI - (FAMOUS FOR TAKOYAKI IS A SNACK MADE FROM BATTER, OCTOPUS, TEMPURA (TENKASU), GINGER AND ONION)</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', '');
