(840, 19, 98, 1910, 'Athens', 'GREECE', 'ATHENS', 'waste-incineration-266929_640.jpg', 'waste-incineration-266929_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">The city of Athens has long played an influential role in the world. The city has a significant and interesting history, as it is Europe&rsquo;s historic capital as well as the capital of modern Greece. The city has been occupied by many conquerors throughout the centuries and many of these erected stunning monuments. Today the city is a bustling, modern metropolis, but charming historical features lie just below the surface. The historic city centre has been turned into a large pedestrian zone that provides access to many of the main archaeological parks, including the temple of Olympian Zeus, Hadrian&rsquo;s Arch, the ancient Theatre of Dionysis and many other sites. Athens is the capital and the largest city of Greece with its history of about 7000 years, an amalgamation of historic and the modern world can be seen throughout the city. Thanks to the 2004 Olympics, Athens is in much better shape than before. The city of Athens is surrounded by 4 large mountains Mt. Aigaleo to the west, Mt. Parnitha to the north, Mt. Pentelicus to the northeast and Mt. Hymettus to the east. The earliest settlements here began over 7000 years ago. Naturally, it became a centre for rulers to establish their kingdoms. Athens boasts of having two UNECSO world heritage sites, the Acropolis and Daphni monastery. The city is very vibrant. There are diverse options for shopping ranging from colourful bazaars to suburban malls. With an efficient transport system, exploring this great city is not a hassle at all. A symbol of Western Civilization at its most magnificent, Athens boasts an illustrious history that stretches back more than 3000 years. The city flourished during classical antiquity and was the birthplace of Socrates, Pericles and Sophocles. More than just a relic of its glorious past, today Athens is a bustling and modern capital city. The Acropolis is one of the world&#39;s most breathtaking ancient ruins and the city&#39;s exceptional archaeology museums display fascinating artefacts uncovered at local sites.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><br />\r\nAthens, being a tourist destination, offers places to stay in a full wide range of price spectrum. Plaka is the most popular choice for travellers. Most of the luxurious hotels are around Syntagma. Some affordable and excellent hotels are in the quiet neighbourhood of Makrygianni and Koukaki. Best places quickly fill up in the peak seasons of July and August. There are more than 350 hotels in the Greater Athens metropolitan area, ranging from backpackers&#39; hostels to five star beach resorts and from historic landmark buildings to contemporary high rises. The most important choice is about the location of the hotel. This decision is important in such a large city, considering the traffic jams that appear in certain areas at different times of the day.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air </strong>- Athens airport is a major hub for East Mediterranean regions. All major airlines including Air Canada, Eithad, Gulf Air, Emirates and Qatar Airways have flights for Athens.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- he rail service is quite poor in Greece compared to other European countries. In effect, Greece has only two train lines which connect Athens to other cities. Metro service in Athens is very efficient and effective. It covers most of the city. The tram system connects the centre of city to southern suburbs and has connections to metro lines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road </strong>- Bear in mind that Greece has one of the highest car accident rates in Europe. Drivers treat red lights as optional and passing on curves and hills seems to be the norm rather than the rare exception. Athens can be reached by E-75 from the north which hugs the eastern coast and by E-65 from the west.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus </strong>- The bus system in Athens has recently been upgraded to make the journey pleasant and safe. At times, there is collaboration between bus and train services of neighbouring countries like Turkey, Bulgaria and Serbia for passengers to commute.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water </strong>- The ancient port of Pireas is still functional and also severs as an exit point for the city. It connects domestic destinations like Aegean islands except the Sporades and some smaller Cyclades and Dodecanese isles that require another connection. International destinations which connect Athens include Cyprus and the Middle East.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - All the prominent places in Athens are fairly connected via bus network, metro services, tram and waterways. Tourist cabs and Uber are also available easily to travel around Athens. Most of Athens main tourist attractions are centrally located making it extremely convenient for walking.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - ATHENS - {FAMOUS FOR MOUSSAKA IS A DISH MADE FROM EGGPLANT OR POTATOES AND MINCED MEAT ; PASTITSIO IS A TYPE OF PASTA MADE FROM GROUND BEEF AND BECHAMEL SAUCE ; SPANAKOPITA IS A PIE MADE FROM PHYLLO, SPINACH, RICOTTA, ONIONS AND EGGS}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - ACROPOLIS MUSEUM CAFE AND RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT ACROPOLIS MUSEUM, DIONYSIOU AREOPAGITOU 15 - (FAMOUS FOR BRIAM IS A ROASTED VEGETABLES MADE FROM EGGPLANT, GARLIC, ONIONS, POTATOES, TOMATOES, AND ZUCCHINI)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - MPAKALOTAVERNA, LOCATED AT THOUKIDIDOU 6, CHALANDRI - (FAMOUS FOR HORIATIKI IS A GREEK SALAD MADE FROM TOMATOES, CUCUMBERS, ONIONS, FETA CHEESE, OLIVES, SALT, OREGANO AND OLIVE OIL)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(841, 19, 98, 1911, 'Thessaloniki', 'GREECE', 'THESSALONIKI', 'greece-2736502_6401.jpg', 'greece-2736502_6402.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Thessaloniki is the second largest city in Greece and also is one of the most popular tourist destinations in the country. Thessaloniki offers the cosmopolitan culture and energy of a big city with the friendly ambience and charm of a smaller town. It&#39;s a wonderful destination to experience the real Greece without the crowds and congestion of Athens. This delightful city has an impressive multiethnic heritage, influenced by the different civilizations that have left their mark, including the Romans, Venetians and Ottoman Turks. Visitors are awed by the ancient ruins, Byzantine churches and the world class archaeology museum, one of the best in Greece. Another highlight is the delicious local cuisine top rated restaurants tantalize diners with region&#39;s finest culinary fare. Thessaloniki is also famous for its music scene and lives band performances that take place at venues throughout the city at almost any time of the year. Situated at the head of the Gulf of Thessalon&iacute;k, it seems open to the rest of the world, with a wide ethnic mix and an air of general prosperity, stimulated by a major university and a famously avant garde live music and entertainment scene. The food is better here too and there are some very sophisticated restaurants, but also wholesome traditional food on offer in a great number of old fashioned Turkish influenced ouzeris and tavernas. The city has enough to offer the visitor for two or three days, at least. There are substantial Roman remains and the many churches constitute a showcase of Orthodox architecture through the ages, while one can catch glimpses of the Turkish city both in the walled Upper City and in the modern grid of streets below. This second largest city in Greece dates back to 315 BC and is the capital of Central Macedonia. Through several thousand years Thessaloniki has attained a large collection of iconic buildings from Byzantine, Paleochristian, Roman, Ancient Greek, Ottoman and Sephardic Jewish origins. It has been known as vibrant centre of festivals and culture and has one of the most inventive nightlife scenes in Greece. Anyone who visits Thessaloniki with a love of history, archaeology or world religions will be astounded by the many monuments to discover here.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">If came to Thessaloniki to splurge and pamper, book a room at one of the city&#39;s five star hotels, providing spacious rooms packed with amenities, as well as access to rooftop bars, ground floor restaurants and fitness facilities. Centrally located hotels also provide secure parking, complimentary Wi-Fi and quick walking access to the city&#39;s top attractions. On the other hand, if all needed is a comfortable bed and a warm meal, consider a budget friendly hostel or family run inn in the residential areas outside the city&#39;s central area. Like any city there are hotels of every category. There is a youth Hostel where beds are cheap. There is also a campground at the beach of Agia Triada, but it&#39;s 27 kilometres away and limits the nightlife.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air </strong>- Thessaloniki is linked to Athens, Ioannina, Hania, Heraklion, Lemnos, Lesvos, Rhodes and Skiathos. The city&#39;s airport 16 kms outside Thessaloniki is international and served by many of the major airlines. Tourists can even fly here from the USA.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - Rail services link Thessaloniki with, Athens and the towns of Macedonia and Thrace. The line through what was once Yugoslavia provides connections with Central and Western Europe. The line through Bulgaria connects to Eastern Europe and the line through Istanbul, Turkey with the countries of the near East.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Coach services are operated by KTEL between Thessaloniki and Athens, Larissa, Volos, Patras and Aedipsos. The trip from Athens to Thessaloniki takes about 6 hours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water</strong> - Apparently the ferry service to and from various islands has been suspended. However there is ferry service connecting Kavala to Athens and various islands and tourists can take a bus to and from Kavala to Thessaloniki.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - In general transportation inside Thessaloniki city and its suburbs is well organised and there are buses to serve the travellers. The taxis in Thessaloniki have a dark blue and white colour and are easily found in every corner of the city. They are reliable and they run all day and night long but they are more expensive than urban buses. If don&#39;t want to drive or wait for the bus, a private transfer is the way to go. Passenger cars, minivans and minibuses are available.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - NEGROPONTE, LOCATED AT KATOUNI 21 - (FAMOUS FOR FRIED-PORK WITH YOGURT AND ZUCCHINI CAKES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - MOLYVOS RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT IONOS DRAGOUMI 31 - (FAMOUS FOR CHUNKIER BEJENDI, SMALL PIECES OF VEAL IN EGGPLANT PUREE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - SEMPRIKO, LOCATED AT FRAGKON 2 - (FAMOUS FOR LAMB MEAT AND YOGURT)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - LOLA, LOCATED AT AGAPINOU 10 - (FAMOUS FOR SEAFOOD DISHES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - DIAVASI, LOCATED AT P. MELA 13 - (FAMOUS FOR SOUTZOUKAKIA IS A TYPE OF STEW MADE FROM MEAT (BEEF), BREAD CRUMBS, EGG, GARLIC, PARSLEY, CUMIN, CINNAMON, SALT, AND PEPPER)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>6 - NEA FOLIA, LOCATED AT 546 34, ARISTOMENOUS 4 - (FAMOUS FOR GRILLED CHICKEN CHOPS)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(842, 19, 98, 1912, 'Olympia', 'GREECE', 'OLYMPIA', 'column-855102_640.jpg', 'column-855102_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Olympia is one of the most significant archaeological sites in the country. Olympia was the home to first ancient Olympic Games, which consisted of members representing each Greek city state in several athletic competitions. The Ancient Stadium in Olympia provides visitors with the opportunity to imagine what it might have been like to observe or even participate in the original games. Near the stadium, the ancient Greeks constructed a sanctuary to Zeus. Other interesting sites include the palaestra and the workshop of Phedias and the Archaeological Museum. The nearby village offers a range of amenities for tourists as well as plenty of relaxing green spaces to unwind after a day exploring the ancient sites. Nearly three thousand years have passed since this area held the first Olympic Games in the shadow of the stately Mount Kronos, a tribute to the god, Zeus. The remains of temples honouring both Zeus and Hera can be found here, their graceful columns offering a picturesque ruin where one can wander freely. The flame for the modern Olympic Games is still lit in front of the Temple of Hera. The centrepiece of the site is the 200 mts track of the stadium itself, entered by way of a long arched tunnel. The vast sanctuary complex built to house competitors thousands of years ago has yielded a wealth of artefacts, exhibited in the on-site Olympia Archaeological Museum. The site itself is picturesque, but the sheer quantity of ruined structures can give a confusing impression of their ancient grandeur and function despite the crowds, tour buses, souvenir shops and other trappings of mass tourism, it deserves a visit with at least an overnight stay at the modern village of Olymbia. Modern Olympia, an attractive mountain town surrounded by pleasant hilly countryside, has hotels and taverns, convenient for visitors to the ancient site.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Despite its small size, Olympia features a lively main street lined by hotels offering comfortable rooms and quick access to one of Greece&#39;s most popular archaeological sites. If don&#39;t mind driving to Olympia&#39;s famous ruins, explore the area&#39;s seaside hotels, where spacious rooms come with access to fine restaurants, fitness facilities, spa treatments, private beaches and outdoor swimming pools. Tourists can also visit the ancient sites from a budget friendly hotel in Pyrgos, a lively town just northwest of Olympia. The hotels in Olympia offer great accommodation and affordable rates for tourists.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - There is no airport in Olympia. The nearest airports are located in Patra and Athens. The airport of Patra works only in summer and receives charters and low cost flights from abroad. The airport of Athens receives domestic and international flights all year round.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - In summer, there is a tourist train from Katakolon to Olympia. This train runs once or twice per day and it was mainly constructed to serve the millions of cruise passengers who arrive in the port of Katakolon and want to visit Ancient Olympia.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - There are daily buses from Athens to Olympia via Pyrgos. Buses depart from Kifissos KTEL Station in Athens and go to Pyrgos frequently, about 4-5 times per day. In Pyrgos, visitors have to take another bus to Olympia. The bus trip from Athens to Pyrgos is about 4 hours and from Pyrgos to Olympia is 45 minutes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Car</strong> - If want to drive from Athens to Olympia take the national road that goes from Athens to Patra and then continue to Pyrgos. At Pyrgos, take the signs to Olympia. In general this road is highway but has large parts where attention is needed. The road trip from Athens to Olympia is about 4 hours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - &nbsp;Visitors have a number of options for getting around while visiting Olympia Greece and include by car, bus, train or taxi. &nbsp;However, most of these options for transportation are best found in Athens or Pyrgos a neighbouring town to Olympia. A personal vehicle is the most convenient form of transportation available for exploring Olympia as it allows the greatest freedom and flexibility in travel. &nbsp;Although Olympia is a major stop on many tours around Greece and there are numerous public transportation options for getting there, a car is the easiest way of getting around.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - AUTHENTIC GREEK STREET FOOD, LOCATED AT 36, ARCHEA OLIMPIA - (FAMOUS FOR SALADS AND PASTA)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n2 - SYMPOSIO TAVERN, LOCATED AT AIMILIOU KOYNTSE - (FAMOUS FOR GYRO IS A TYPE OF SANDWICH MADE FROM MEAT: BEEF, VEAL, MUTTON, PORK, OR CHICKEN)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - AEGEAN RESTAURANT CAF&Eacute;,LOCATED AT 4, ARCHEA - (FAMOUS FOR BAKLAVA IS A &nbsp;DESSERT PASTRY MADE FROM FILO DOUGH, NUTS, SWEETENED WITH SYRUP OR HONEY)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - MARE RESTAURANT CORFU, LOCATED AT GOUVIA, MARINA, CORFU - (FAMOUS FOR PASTA AND FISH DISHES)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>5 - STREET FOOD, LOCATED AT MYLOPOTAMOS - (FAMOUS FOR BURGER)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(843, 19, 98, 1913, 'Crete', 'GREECE', 'CRETE', 'crete-2651290_640.jpg', 'crete-2651290_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">The largest island in Greece, Crete is a little country in itself. Home to glorious beaches, impressive landscapes and traces of magnificent civilizations, Crete boasts a scenic interior, with the Samaria gorge, and a rich gastronomic culture. Crete, the largest of the Greek islands and the fifth biggest island in the Mediterranean, lies 318 kilometres south of Athens&#39; port, Piraeus. Rimmed by more than 1000 kilometres of coastline, it combines dramatic mountains with deep rocky gorges and blissful golden sand beaches. The most southerly outpost of Europe, its south coast extends to the Libyan Sea, looking to Africa, while cultural influences from Asia Minor can also be felt from the period spent under Turkish rule. Thanks to its fertile soils and warm, sunny climate, the local economy is based on agriculture, with tourism coming in a strong second. Crete&#39;s ancient archaeological sites, centuries old harbour towns, and beaches attract visitors from all over the world. Crete is a magical tapestry of splendid beaches, ancient treasures, and landscapes encompassing vibrant cities and dreamy villages, where locals share their traditions, wonderful cuisine and generous spirit. Crete is the largest island in Greece, and the fifth largest one in the Mediterranean Sea. Here, tourists can admire the remnants of brilliant civilizations, explore glorious beaches, impressive mountains capes, fertile valleys and steep gorges and become part of the island&rsquo;s rich gastronomic culture. Crete is, after all, a small universe teeming with beauties and treasures that one will probably need a lifetime to uncover. Crete was once the centre of Minoan civilization which is regarded as the earliest civilization of Europe. Crete is mountainous with its range crossing from west to east. The island also contains beautiful gorges, rivers and lakes and is surrounded by a large number of islands. If there is a contest among the most beautiful islands in the world, Crete will surely be a major contender for the title.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">There is plethora of lodging facilities available on the island in all the parts. Options include apartments and apart-hotels, hotels in a wide spectrum of range, villas and private homes. Tourists can see rent room signs at almost every home there. These are rarely advertised on the internet and one can make advance reservations if have someone local staying there. The island hosts a wide variety of lodgings to fit practically any budget and with a little research anyone can find the Crete accommodation that fits best. There are the general 5 star lavish luxury hotels that can be found in plenty throughout Europe on the island of Crete and these are the easiest options to choose. There are several different towns in Crete each offering a wide variety of accommodation choices for every type of traveller.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - Tourists can fly to Athens and from there take summer charter flights to Crete which will land in the city of Heraklion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water</strong> - To reach Crete by boat, board it from Athens which will drop on one of the 6 ports located at Heraklion, Chania, Rethymno, and Kastelli-Kissamou. Crete connects through these ports with Piraeus, Santorini, Sikinos and more ports around Athens.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around </strong>- Tourists can easily rent a car in Crete and Cretans drive on the right hand side of the road so it can be a challenge. Taxis are also available but that can be bit expensive. Buses are quite frequent and trustworthy. Bus services along the north coast and south are excellent and cheap. Since there are no roads along the southwest coast, there is a ferry line between Paleochora, Sougia, Agia Poumeli, Loutro and Hora sfakion.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - CRETE - {FAMOUS FOR DAKOS IS A TYPE OF SALAD MADE FROM DRIED BREAD OR BARLEY RUSK, TOMATOES, CHEESE, OREGANO, HERBS AND OLIVES ; KALITSOUNIA IS A TYPE OF PIE MADE FROM &nbsp;FLOUR, MIZITHRA AND HONEY ; LOUKOUMADES IS A DESERT MADE FROM DRY YEAST, WATER, VEGETABLE OIL, LEMON JUICE, SUGAR, SALT, FLOUR AND EGGS}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - MAMA&#39;S DINNER RESTAURANT, LOCATED AT KALIVIANI, KISSAMOS - (FAMOUS FOR SEAFOOD &nbsp;AND GRILLED LAMB)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - GEORGIA&#39;S TRADITIONAL TAVERNA, LOCATED AT EPAR. OD. GEORGIOUPOLIS-KOURNAS LAKE KOURNA, KOURNAS, APOKORONAS - (FAMOUS FOR BURGER)</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(844, 19, 98, 1914, 'Thessaly', 'GREECE', 'THESSALY', 'greece-2719383_640.jpg', 'greece-2719383_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Thessaly is one of the thirteen administrative divisions of Greece. It is located in the central part of the country. In the past, during the Mycenaen period it was known as Aeolia. Enjoy Thessaly, a region of sheer beauty with mountains, rivers, beaches, the Sporades Islands complex, the popular Plastira Lake, Tempi valley and last but not least the unique Meteora, the most photogenic spiritual site in Greece. Archaeological areas, Byzantine monasteries and churches, traditional settlements and ski resorts complete the fascinating natural beauty of Thessaly and make it a popular holiday destination. The peninsula of Pelion has the most beautiful Thessaly villages. Makrinitsa, Portaria and Tsagarada are the most famous mountainous villages in Thessaly, while all along the interior and exterior coastline of the peninsula, there are lovely seaside villages that get very busy in summer. Very beautiful are also the Thessaly villages of Meteora in Thessaly, particularly Kalambaka and Kastraki. Constructed on the foot of the giant rocks, the villages of Meteora get popular all year round for their tourist facilities. Between the mountains of Epirus and the blue magnificence of the Aegean, amid the bushes and trees of Thessaly plain, perched on the massive slopes of Olympus and Oeta Mountains, where the battle between the Gods and the Titans took place, the countryside of Thessaly will leave tourists speechless. Above the region of Central Greece, lovely Thessaly unveils its mysteries with the most enigmatic way. Bordered with the vastness of the Aegean Sea, Thessaly is a truly inspiring region where even Lord himself would wander how could possibly all these landscapes of extreme natural beauty coexist so harmonically. Although Thessaly may have far fewer miles of drop dead gorgeous coastline than southern magic of the country, visitors should undoubtedly bring their hiking boots and their swimming suits to discover the mysterious, unseen face of the mountains, the folkloric villages, the lush valleys and the emerald beaches that will make up for it.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Although most visitors to Thessaly flock to one of the island&#39;s beach resorts, staying outside the tourist driven areas allows choosing from less expensive rooms without compromising on comfort and proximity to the beach. Consider a self catering apartment or small villa just outside Skiathos Town or look for a budget friendly room in one of the city&#39;s family run inns. Another quiet and affordable alternative, the small settlements scattered along the island&#39;s coastline offer simple lodgings and plenty of privacy within driving distance of major urban attractions.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - In Thessaly the only airport currently operating is Volos airport situated in Nea-Anchialos, about 30 kms southwest from the city of Volos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- Trains connect Volos, Larissa and Kalampaka with the rest of Greece. Travelling with ordinary trains can be cheaper, although a little bit slower, whereas choosing a fancy faster Intercity train will cost the same amount of money or even more than a KTEL bus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus </strong>- KTEL buses are by far the most convenient way to travel around Greece, as well as for intra regional travelling. From Athens most of buses to Thessaly leaves from Terminal B, at Liossion Street.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - There are twelve bus lines going around the city detailed info in the regional bus terminal, directly adjacent to the Interurban Bus Terminal. Taxis in Thessaly as everywhere in Greece are comparably cheap. Most of Thessaly is quite flat, that makes it very easy for cycling and a lot of locals do cycle.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - THESSALY - {FAMOUS FOR TIROKAFTERI IS A TYPE OF SPREAD MADE FROM &nbsp;CHEESE, &nbsp;PEPPERS, OLIVE OIL, LEMON JUICE, GARLIC, YOGURT AND OREGANO ; TZATZIKI IS A TYPE OF SOUP MADE FROM STRAINED YOGURT, CUCUMBERS, GARLIC, OLIVE OIL, SALT, &nbsp;LEMON JUICE, DILL, MINT, OR PARSLEY ; PASTITSIO IS A PASTA MADE FROM GROUND BEEF, BECHAMEL SAUCE ; KOKORETSI IS A TYPE OF MEAT DISH MADE FROM LAMB OR GOAT INTESTINE&#39;S, OFFAL (SWEETBREADS, HEARTS, LUNGS OR KIDNEYS}</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>2 - TAVERNA SELINI, LOCATED AT ALEX MORAITIDOU STREET - (FAMOUS FOR SEAFOOD)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - O PARAXENOS, LOCATED AT &Epsilon;UAYYEIOTPIAC 9, SKIATHOS - (FAMOUS FOR MOUSSAKA IS A DISH MADE FROM EGGPLANT OR POTATOES AND MINCED MEAT)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>4 - PUB 38, LOCATED AT 28IS OKTOVRIOU 18, KALAMPAKA - (FAMOUS FOR HAMBURGER, CHOCLATE CAKE)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(845, 19, 98, 1915, 'Epirus', 'GREECE', 'EPIRUS', 'parga-1163344_640.jpg', 'parga-1163344_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Rugged mountains, hidden bays, traditional villages, natural beauty and exhilarating activities meet the myriad faces of Epirus. In Epirus the people seem to blend in with the land. One will meet a different Greece at this crossroads of civilisations and landscapes in Western Greece, between the Pindos mountain range and the Ionian Sea. Mountain peaks, gorges, rare plants and animals, lakes, rivers and indented sandy beaches complement the ancient ruins of Dodoni and dozens of mediaeval castles, monasteries, arched bridges and stone built traditional villages. The destinations are many and varied, creating a wide range of options for holidays all year round. From picturesque Zagorohoria, Metsovo and the Tzoumerka, to beautiful Ioannina and the summer resorts of Parga and Syvota, Epirus welcome tourists at any time of year and deliver on its promise of an unforgettable experience. On the sandy shores of the endless Epirot coastline in Western Greece, from Preveza to Parga, tourists will find beach bars to serve drinks and summer spirit. High mountains and rushing rivers offer plenty of adrenaline pumping excitement. The history of Epirus is unbelievably rich. It&rsquo;s all there to behold at the magnificent archaeological site of Dodoni with its famous ancient theatre, at Roman Nikopolis and at the Oracle at Efyra, renowned in antiquity. Throughout Epirus one will admire traditional workmanship in crafts of all kinds, from stone masonry to the delicate art of the silversmith. Discover the wonderful unspoilt villages, which have been dubbed poetry in stone because of their exceptional architecture, like those in the Zagoria district, Metsovo, Syrrako and Kalarrytes in the Tzoumerka range. Zitsa is known for its sparkling wine and bottled water, which is sold under the names Vikos and Tzoumerka.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Most hotels in Epirus are found in the tourist spots of the region including Parga, Zagoria, Ioannina, Sivota and Preveza. The cosy guesthouses lying within Ioannina&#39;s citadel, up winding cobbled alley where feature includes exposed stone walls and an alluring courtyard complete with its own old well and rates offer excellent value for money. The boutique hotels are relaxing place to stay within the city&#39;s historic citadel, offering seven light and bright rooms complete with Jacuzzi in the mini-bar. The resorts offer unrivalled views of mountainous coastline, a string of verdant islets and a pool perfect for spotting dolphins out at sea or for sunset views of nearby Corfu and Paxos.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The two airports of Epirus are located in Ioannina and Preveza. The airport of Ioannina receives only domestic flights from Athens. The airport of Preveza works only in summer and receives charter flights from abroad.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus </strong>- Buses to towns of Epirus depart from Kifissos KTEL Station in Athens. There are buses to the largest towns of the region, while there are also internal buses to smaller towns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water</strong> - The largest port of Epirus is Igoumenitsa, which receives ferries from Italy and also serves ferries to the islands of Corfu and Paxi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around </strong>- The cities in Epirus are small enough to travel through via foot. The buses are blue and white at various shades. The Taxis at Epirus has dark green colour. Rental car is the most efficient mode of transportation. Road bikers are also catered for as high quality road bikes with free delivery are available for rent with them also.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - IONION, LOCATED AT &nbsp;VOLA - (FAMOUS FOR CRAB CAKES)<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n2 - TAVERNA STEFANOS, LOCATED AT &nbsp;MAVROGIANNI 7, PARGA - (FAMOUS FOR SEAFOOD)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>3 - ACHILLEAS BAKERY, LOCATED AT PARGA 480 60 - (FAMOUS FOR PASTRIES AND SANDWICHES)</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(846, 19, 98, 1916, 'Central Greece', 'GREECE', 'CENTRAL GREECE', 'village-2729360_640.jpg', 'village-2729360_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Central Greece, called by the Greeks Sterea Ellada, is a large geographical area which, as the name says, is centrally located in Greece. The surface of the Sterea Ellada is approximately 25000 sq kms. Central Greece is the place where heart of true Greece beats while being enchanted by the variations of its landscape. Historical landmarks and monuments, stone built settlements, the Oracle of Delphi, exciting hiking trails, national parks, ski resorts; beaches with turquoise waters, traditional customs and flavours all tell the story of one of the most beautiful regions in Greece. The central Greece region also holds many underrated surprises. Alpine meadows and valleys cover the Evritania mountain range, making it perfect for breezy summer hikes and winter skiing. And it doesn&rsquo;t get much better than the beautiful Pelion Peninsula, home to Jason and the Argonauts and criss crossed with historic cobble stone paths linking lush mountain hamlets with coves and beaches that rival the best islands. Heroic Thermopylae, a stone&rsquo;s throw from Kamena Vourla and its famous spas, reminds us of the sacrifice made by Leonidas and his 300 Spartans. In Viotia, the byzantine monastery of Osios Loukas with its renowned mosaics is yet another important monument, included in UNESCO World Heritage list. Mount Parnassos, one of the renowned National Parks in Greece and also known as the Mountain of the Light, is covered with thick forests of black pine and Kefalonian fir. Discover the dozens of trails hidden in its lush nature as well as the famous Corycian Cave, the place where the Nymphs and the Greek god Pan were worshipped during antiquity. Central Greece offers a huge range of activities from below sea level to the peaks of imposing mountains all year round. Besides the breathtaking natural beauty and beaches, this holiday destination is also famous for its authentic local flavours. Among the most popular are katiki a soft fresh cheese from Domokos and the famous form aella and homemade pasta from Arahova.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />\r\nDespite its popularity with tourists, Central Greece offers plenty of affordable hotel lodgings even at peak season, though one must book early if want a room with a view of the Gulf of Corinth. Travellers looking for budget friendly options can try one of the area&#39;s inns, where friendly service and easy access to good shops and restaurants compensate for a lack of modern amenities. Alternatively, visit Central Greece ancient sites from one of the boutique hotels clinging to the slopes of nearby Mount Parnassus. There are very nice modern hotels with magnificent view of the cities of Central Greece and the Corinthian Gulf.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align: justify;"><br />\r\n<strong>By Air</strong> - There are a few airports in central and northern Greece. The major one is in Volos, known as Volos Central Greece Airport or Nea-Anchialos National Airport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Train </strong>- Thessaloniki is Greece&#39;s hub for international rail service. Trains connect Thessaloniki to Sofia, Bucharest, Istanbul and Belgrade via Skopje. From Athens the train connects most of the cities in the eastern part of Greece.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Road </strong>- Central Greece can be entered by car either from any of its land neighbouring countries or from Athens. From Western Europe, the most popular route to Greece was through Yugoslavia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Bus </strong>- There is some, albeit limited, international bus service to neighbouring Albania, Bulgaria and Turkey, as well as Georgia. From Athens there are buses to every town in Central Greece.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>By Water </strong>- The main port to get to Central Greece from Italy is Igoumenitsa. Several ferries depart daily from the Italian port cities of Venice, Ancona, Bari and Brindisi.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;"><strong>Getting Around </strong>- Interurban coaches are by far the most convenient way to travel around Central Greece, as well as for intra regional travelling. Trains connects most of the towns on the central part of Greece. The towns in Central Greece are small enough that walking is really the only means of transportation required. Taxis however are readily available.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', ''),
(847, 19, 99, 1917, 'Vienna', 'AUSTRIA', 'VIENNA', 'vienna-674855_6401.jpg', 'vienna-674855_6402.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">The capital of Austria is home to nearly one third of the county&rsquo;s inhabitants and is its primary city. This metropolitan city hosts the United Nations organisation and is a major centre for Austria&rsquo;s culture, economy and Politics. With many different names like the City of Music and the City of dreams, Vienna is renowned throughout the world and has a plethora of stunning historical buildings, gardens and establishments. Ranked as one of the most liveable cities in the world with its inhabitants enjoying a high quality of life, Vienna is a heaven in central Europe and remains a popular tourist destination. The capital city of the republic of Austria and unmistakably one of the most visited cities of Europe Vienna is sprawling with raw beauty and charm of its own. Shadowed by its rich history, one can see the reflection of the past all across the city through grand historic buildings and well preserved culture. Nestled on the banks of the beautiful Danube River, Vienna served as an entryway between West and East Europe for centuries. Today, it is one of the most impressive commercial and cultural hubs of the country offering some remarkable historic sites, museums, live events and entertainment. Vienna is a city that has given the rest of the world some very precious things the graceful Viennese waltz, delicate and deliciously sinful pastries and a few great classical composers. But Austria&rsquo;s capital and largest city has also provided the world with its fair share of historical personalities and moments. It is a city that represents refinement and culture to visitors, who will not lack for things to do. Vienna has developed from its early Celtic and Roman roots into a medieval and Baroque city, with an old town that was designated a World Heritage Site in 2001. Austria&#39;s multifaceted capital has earned itself several nicknames.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">Some of the greatest hotels in the world are located in Vienna. Hotels range from luxury hotels to bed and breakfasts and inns, and rental apartments and homes. Reservations are recommended as they are required during the peak tourist season in the summer. Less expensive accommodations can be found in some of the districts outside of the centre of the city. It means a ride into the city on a tram, bus or the U-Bahn but the savings on these less expensive accommodations can easily offset transportation costs. Vienna is city with wide range of accommodation options from actual castle and high end luxury hotels to mid range lodgings and hostels. However, one may expect prices on higher side overall as compared to its neighbouring cities and countries even.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air </strong>- The city of Vienna houses an airport of its own located just outside the city limits namely Vienna International Airport. Several international airlines including most of the European countries and plenty of intercontinental airlines ply direct flights to Vienna regularly.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train</strong> - The rail network of Austria is quite efficient, comfortable, reliable and adorned with all sorts of modern facilities. The city of Vienna is home to several major stations with all their names starting with the German word. The southern and the Western main train stations are well connected to the rest of the city where most people arrive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - The streets and highways are in good condition and one can cross the border 24X7 through major crossing points. Getting to Vienna by car or taxi is very easy as taxis are easily available and journey is full of scenic beauty. However, one might have to face heavy traffic especially while entering the city during any hour. It is advisable to use other modes of transport for travelling to Vienna.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Vienna being one of the favourite hotspot for tourists offers several bus services that come into the city on daily basis. There are plenty of international bus services offering huge discounts for particular age groups. There are two major bus stations in Vienna namely Vienna International Bus terminal and Waldmanngronden. There are buses plying to and from many countries including Bratislava, the Czech Republic and Hungary along with local city stops from Vienna International Airport.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Water</strong> - One can also arrive in Vienna through riverboats to and from places such as Linz, Bratislava and Budapest through River Danube but the journey is slow, uncomfortable and quite expensive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around</strong> - Vienna offers an extensive network of public transport managed by the Vienna Transport Authority, which includes trams, rail, commuter rail, buses, subways and taxis. The ways of commuting are inexpensive and quite efficient. Metros or U-Bahn runs daily from 5:00 to 00:30 and all day long on Fridays and Saturdays. Bus service in Vienna mostly serves in suburbs and is not so popular with tourists but night buses that replace the U-Bahn from 00:45 to 05:00 on weekdays are quite handy and cheap. The inner ring is quite compact with lots of pleasant cobblestoned and paved streets.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>1 - VIENNA - {FAMOUS FOR APPLE STRUDEL IS A TYPE OF PASTRY MADE FROM &nbsp;FLOUR, OIL OR BUTTER AND APPLES ; ESTERHAZY TORTE IS A TYPE OF CAKE MADE FROM &nbsp;ALMOND MERINGUE, BUTTERCREAM ; GUGELHUPF IS A TYPE OF CAKE MADE FROM YEAST DOUGH WITH RAISINS, ALMONDS AND KIRSCHWASSER ; KAISERSCHMARRN IS A TYPE OF PANCAKE MADE FROM &nbsp;FLOUR, EGGS, SUGAR, MILK, BUTTER ; PALATSCHINKE IS A DISH MADE FROM EGGS, WHEAT FLOUR, MILK ; TAFELSPITZ IS A DISH MADE FROM BEEF, APPLES AND HORSERADISH ; GOULASH IS A TYPE OF SOUP OR STEW MADE FROM MEAT, NOODLES, VEGETABLES (ESPECIALLY POTATOES), PAPRIKA, SPICES ; SACHERTORTE IS A TYPE OF CAKE MADE FROM CHOCOLATE SPONGE, APRICOT JAM, DARK CHOCOLATE ICING}&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\n2 - CAFE HAWELKA, LOCATED AT &nbsp;DOROTHEERGASSE - (FAMOUS FOR BUCHTELN IS A TYPE SWEET ROLL MADE FROM YEAST DOUGH, JAM, GROUND POPPY SEEDS OR CURD)<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\n3 - CAFE LANDTMANN, LOCATED AT UNIVERSIT&auml;TSRING 4, VIENNA - (FAMOUS FOR PASTRIES AND CAKES)<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', ''),
(848, 19, 99, 1918, 'Salzburg', 'AUSTRIA', 'SALZBURG', 'salzburg-1756367_640.jpg', 'salzburg-1756367_6401.jpg', '<p style="text-align:justify">Situated in central Austria, near the German border, Salzburg is probably best known as the birthplace of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. People come to Austria&rsquo;s fourth largest city from all over the world to view the sights that inspired such unforgettable classical and popular music. With its hill topped medieval fortress, picturesque Altstadt old town and breathtaking Alpine scenery, Salzburg&rsquo;s beauty is sure to enchant visitors in every season of the year. Stretching along the banks of the Salzach River, Salzburg is a historic city that looks as if it was lifted out of a storybook. For those seeking to relive scenes from the 1965 movie the Sound of Music, must see attractions include the 17th century Baroque Mirabell Palace and Gardens, the gazebo in the Schloss Hellbrunn&rsquo;s gardens and the actual von Trapp family home, which is now a hotel. Mozart affectionate can visit his birthplace as well as a reconstruction of his home, complete with period instruments, portraits and musical scores. Rising 120 mts above the city, the Festung Hohensalzbury is a 900 year old fortress built more for show than defence. Although most of the medieval castle&rsquo;s artefacts were taken during the Napoleonic Wars, vistas from the fortress are its real treasures. Visitors can reach the castle by foot or by a quick ride in a 19th century funicular. Whether rambling through Altstadt, the city&rsquo;s old town, marvelling at the abundance of Baroque architecture or relaxing in an open air beer garden sipping a local brew, Salzburg is a travel destination that appeals to all the senses. Salzburg is one of the most renowned cities in Austria and Europe and has possibly the best preserved old town centre full of beautiful baroque architecture which is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The city is slow and magical with music wafting through its streets that are lined with small home run cafes.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify">The lodging opportunities in Salzburg are extensive aside from traditional and modern hotels tourists will also find private bed and breakfasts, campgrounds and farms. Salzburg&#39;s hub offers comfortable accommodations nestled between rich arrays of sights. The Salzach River cuts directly through town, dividing the city into east and west. Look for accommodations in the Altstadt, tucked in between the river and the city&rsquo;s mountain, Monchsberg. For budget minded travellers, try a centrally located youth hostel or small hotel. Tourists can also have choices depending on the preferred location and for easy access to the major attractions a centrally located hotel or hostel is preferable.</p>\r\n', '<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Air</strong> - The Salzburg W.A. Mozart International Airport is the second largest international airport in Austria. Salzburg has direct flight connectivity from a number of cities in Europe. The international airport is only a few kilometres away from the main city centre of the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Train </strong>- Salzburg is located on the Austrian-German border, about two hours from Munich and three hours from Vienna by train. The Salzburg railway station, the Hauptbahnhof, is located to the north of the Salzach River. The intercity trains are frequent, trains from Vienna are especially frequent in intervals of 1 hour.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Bus</strong> - Bus services are efficient and available from Cesky Krumlov, Czech Republic and back. Several kinds of shuttle services can be used. Bus services are present between Prague and Salzburg. It is also possible to reach Salzburg from Budapest through a 5 hour commute.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>By Road</strong> - Salzburg is well connected by roads to Vienna and Munich. Enjoy a picturesque drive through the lakes and villages from Munich to Salzburg. One can drive to Salzburg from Vienna and Munich via Autobahns A-1, the Vienna-Salzburg route and A-8, the Munich-Salzburg route.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><strong>Getting Around </strong>- Taking advantage of its small size, it is convenient to explore the city on foot. Bikes can also be hired from most hotels and hostels. A horse drawn carriage called Fiaker, seats four people. Even though most riders do not know English, it is amusing to try it out if you have never sat on a carriage before. The bus taxis operates along fixed routes, picking up and dropping off passengers along its way. Salzburg trams and buses can be used with the same tickets. Taxis are a reliable source of transport especially if travelling at night.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><br />\r\n<strong>1 - SALZBURG - {FAMOUS FOR SALZBURGER NOCKERL IS A TYPE OF &nbsp;SOUFFLE MADE FROM FLOUR, EGG YOLKS, SUGAR, VANILLA, EGG WHITES ; MOZART BALLS IS A TYPE OF &nbsp;CONFECTIONERY MADE FROM PISTACHIO MARZIPAN, NOUGAT, DARK CHOCOLATE}&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\n2 - BIOBURGERMEISTER, LOCATED AT LINZER G. 54, 5020 - (FAMOUS FOR BURGER)<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\n3 - LE COQ EN PATE, LOCATED AT LINZER G. 72A, 5020 - (FAMOUS FOR CHOCLATE CAKE)<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />\r\n4 - HANA&#39;S RASOI, LOCATED AT GETREIDEGASSE 18 - (FAMOUS FOR BUTTER CHICKEN, TANDOORI ROTI AND MANGO-LASSAI)&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n', '');
